<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Deadline to Surrender Arms to Expire Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian security authorities
today launched a nationwide publicity through radio, television
and news papers to collect illegal arms and ammunition before a
50-day deadline expires Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry announced that the deadline for
delivering the illegal arms to law enforcement agencies would
expire at 24:00 hours local time on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati said earlier that
the decision to collect the firearms and ammunition was made
by the Supreme National Security Council (SNSC).
</P>
<P>
Besharati said those who hold illegal firearms can step
forward and surrender them to law enforcement agencies without
facing charges.
</P>
<P>
He said that the holders would receive receipts upon
surrendering their arms.
</P>
<P>
Today's Persian language daily Akbar reported that some
35,000 illegal arms had been surrendered to the security
departments across the country.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry announced in June that there would be
no punishment and questioning for those who handed over illegal
and hunting arms and ammunition based on an amnesty given by
Iran's Supreme Leader Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
The communique issued by the ministry warned that there
would be severe punishment for those who did not heed the
campaign by the ministry on collection of arms.
</P>
<P>
Those who was found holding illegal arms would have to
serve prison sentences ranging from three to 10 years, it
warned.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian minister said a considerable amount of firearms
were held by individuals during the eight-year war between Iran
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei made the first
order in February this year, asking all Iranians who are in
possession of weapons to hand over them while offering amnesty
to those who are pursued for smuggling of arms in the country.
</P>
<P>
Those who turn in their weapons voluntarily would not be
prosecuted and are given amnesty, according to the order.
</P>
<P>
The Iran-Iraq war once resulted in rumpant arms smuggling in
Iran. Arms are both smuggled in and out of the country through Iran's
border with Iraqi Kurdistan.
</P>
<P>
Light weapons produced by Iran's defense industries are rumored
to be smuggled out of the country because of corruption
and poor management in government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
The sources here said that arms smuggling has always gone
hand in hand with narcotic trade.
</P>
<P>
The smuggling of arms into the country is also attributed
to the main armed opposition to Tehran government by the People's
Mojahedin of Iran (PMOI), a group with bases inside Iraqi
territory.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian officials themselves have become the target of
the weapons and ammunition that are available in arms black
market. Rafsanjani was shot at in 1994 while addressing a
crowd at the mausoleum of late religious leader Ayatollah
Rouhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei was injured and his right hand was forever
paralyzed as a tape record filled with explosives went off
while he was addressing a group of worshippers at a mosque
in 1981. 
</P>
</TEXT>
