<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Arrives in Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein
arrived in Jeddah, a western red sea coastal city in Saudi Arabia,
today for talks for the first time with Saudi King Fahd to forge
ties strained to breaking point by the 1990 Gulf crisis, reports
from Jeddah said.
</P>
<P>
Hussein was welcomed at the Jeddah airport by Saudi King
Fahd, Crown Prince Abdullah Bin Abdul Aziz and other Saudi leaders.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the Jordanian-Saudi summit would
focus on the stalled Middle East peace process, ways to improve
economic cooperation and tighten security links to counter
political violence and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the Jordanian Monarch will also brief
his Saudi counterpart on his recent meetings with Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Syrian President Hafez
Al-Assad and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's ties with Saudi Arabia and other Gulf states
improved dramatically in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Full diplomatic relations between Saudi Arabia and Jordan
were restored in 1995, and economic relations were also
promoted after the exchange of visits between public and
private representatives and the resumption of trade exchange
between the two Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh accused Amman of backing Iraq, expelled Jordanian
diplomats from the Gulf Arab state and recalled its own
ambassador to Jordan in October 1990.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh also punished Jordan by suspending 200 million U.S.
dollar financial aid, stopping oil deliveries and by closing its
markets to Jordanian goods.
</P>
<P>
Today's visit comes amid a diplomatic flurry as Arab leaders
criss-cross the region for urgent talks on the faltering peace
process following the May 29 election of right-wing Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein visited Saudi Arabia in February this year for
the first time since the Gulf crisis in 1990, but the
highest Saudi official he met was the Saudi Crown Prince and
the First Deputy Prime Minister Prince Abdallah Bin Abdel
Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He was not received by King Fahd who was still recovering
from a stroke he suffered in last December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
