<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Urges for Voter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's main opposition party,
the United National Independence Party (UNIP), today urged for the
re-registration of voters for the general elections scheduled for
later this year.
</P>
<P>
UNIP spokesman Rwendo Nulengela said his party opposed the
idea by the ruling Movement for Multi-party Democracy (MMD) to
use voter registers named by the Israeli company, Nikuv, which is
entrusted by the Zambian government to prepare for voter
registration.
</P>
<P>
Nikuv has brought in the registers from the United States,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The UNIP spokesman stressed that if the candidature of former
President and UNIP leader K. Kaunda was not allowed, his party
would also carry out a campaign to boycott the poll. 
</P>
</TEXT>
