<HEADLINE> Pakistan Wants Political Stability in Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani President Farooq
Leghari said today that Pakistan wants peace and political
stability in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Talking to a high-level Afghan government delegation led by
Afghan Interior Minister Younas Qanooni, Leghari expressed the
hope that leaders of all the political factions in Afghanistan
would soon start working for peace.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan has nothing but love, affection and respect for the
Afghan people as they have suffered more than any other nation in
the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan does not want hegemony in Afghanistan but would
rather build bridges of cooperation and friendship based on
commonality of mutual interest," the president said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Leghari said, was looking forward to the Pakistani
diplomatic presence in Kabul again to further facilitate contacts
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan is also looking forward to the opening of
trade routes as well as the establishment of rail and road links.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan delegation also met with Pakistani Prime Minister
Benazir Bhutto.
</P>
<P>
Qanooni asked Pakistan to reopen its mission in Kabul and said
the Afghan side would provide full security and administrative
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan closed its embassy in Kabul after it was burnt last
September by a group of armed people.
</P>
<P>
Benazir assured the Afghan minister that Pakistan would work
together with the United Nations and other countries in the region
to achieve a consensus on Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan delegation arrived here on Saturday for talks with
the Pakistani government on supply of petroleum and food stuffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
