<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One killed in Clashes Between Greek, Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 11 (Xinhua) -- One people was killed and
several others were injured in clashes today between Greek and
Turkish Cypriots in the U.N.-controlled buffer zone on this East
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
The incident came following a Greek Cypriot anti-Turkish
motorcycle demonstration, which started from Berlin on August 2.
</P>
<P>
Several thousand motorcyclists were attempting to cross into
the Turkish-controlled areas and to ride to northern coastal town
of Kyrenia.
</P>
<P>
But the final stage of the ride was cancelled today for
"political and security reasons" at the request of Cyprus
President Glafcos Clerides.
</P>
<P>
However, many motorcyclists refused to heed the call by their
leadership and together with other Greek Cypriots broke into the
U.N.-controlled buffer zone and were involved in scuffles with
the Turkish Cypriots, also in the buffer zone.
</P>
<P>
Tasos Isaac, 24, from Paralimni village on the eastern coast,
was trapped in barbed wire in the buffer zone and then beaten by
several Turkish Cypriots. He died on the way to hospital,
according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
Several others were also injured and taken to hospital for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
U.N. peace-keeping force spokesman Waldemar Rokoszweski was
quoted as saying that the U.N. "has limited resources and cannot
therefore keep an eye on every spot along the buffer zone".
</P>
<P>
He said some 1,000 out of around 1,200 U.N. peace-keepers on
the island were deployed for possible incidents in today's
demonstration.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. spokesman also indirectly criticized the Cypriot
authorities and the Turkish Cypriot regime for not "being able to
stop their respective civilians from encroaching the buffer
zone".
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides, in a
televised address to the nation, expressed satisfaction with the
compliance of the Cyprus Motorcycle Federation with his request
to cancel the last part of today's anti-Turkish rally.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
control of 37 percent of the island following an Athens-backed
coup.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. peace-keeping force has been patrolling along the
180-kilometer-long buffer zone separating the Turkish troops from
the Greek Cypriot National Guards. 
</P>
</TEXT>
