<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-11 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Omani Minister of Trade on New Seven-Nation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Omani Minister of Trade
and Industry Maqboul Bin Ali Sultan has disclosed that seven
countries overlooking the Indian Ocean, including Oman, will meet
in Mauritius next September to discuss final arrangements for the
establishment of an economic bloc.
</P>
<P>
In an interview today with the Omani daily "Al Watan", the
Omani Minister said that Mauritius, India, South Africa, Kenya,
Singapore, Australia and Oman possess the potentials of
integration, including cheap and skilled labor as well as raw
materials such as coal in Australia, gas in Oman and services in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Such integration will be of direct help to these states
and will also help them benefit from the World Trade Organization,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that preliminary meetings on the establishment of
this bloc were held in Mauritius, adding that Omani Minister of
State for Foreign Affairs Youssef Alawi had recently visited
Mauritius and India to discuss necessary arrangements.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the seven-nation bloc will start
functioning with gradual cooperation in the fields of tourism and
trade, ultimately expanding into a full-fledged economic bloc. It
will thus be possible for the group to provide huge investments
and also prompt increase in exports and imports as well as joint
ventures among the member states.
</P>
<P>
The Omani Minister added that the new bloc of Indian Ocean
states would not be restricted to the seven founding members, but
might incorporate other states such as Yemen and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that the membership of Oman in the bloc would
link the group with the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states, in
the best interest of all parties.
</P>
<P>
The GCC groups Oman, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, the United
Arab emirates and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
