<HEADLINE> Egypt's Oil Production Drops in First Half of 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's oil production dropped in
the first half of this year by 642,000 tons, according to a
government report.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by the Cabinet Information and
Decision-Support Center, said that Egypt produced 21,684,000 tons
of oil from January to June this year, compared with 22,326,000
tons in the first six months of 1995.
</P>
<P>
The average daily production of crude oil ranges from 870,000
barrels to 900,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
But the country's production of natural gas increased,
according to figures given by the Egyptian Middle East News
Agency (MENA) today.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Egypt produced 5,227,000 tons
of gas, an increase of 333,000 tons over the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
Gas consumption in the country also increased in the first six
months of 1996. Egypt used 4.683 million tons of gas, compared with
4.503 million tons over the corresponding period of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been trying to reduce oil consumption by relying more
on gas so that more oil can be exported. Oil revenues are the
fourth largest source of Egypt's foreign currency income behind
overseas remittances, tourism and the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, revenues from the Suez
Canal tolls dropped by 50.6 million U.S. dollars, from 976.8
million dollars in the first half of last year to 926.2 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The drop in revenues resulted from the decreasing number of
ships and oil tankers passing through the canal, which links the
Mediterranean and the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
According to the report carried by MENA, 7,419 ships transited
the 193-kilometer-long canal in the first half of this year
compared to 7,617 in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The tourism industry has continued to pick up this year,
according to the report on Egypt's economic performance in the
first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
Tourism revenues from January to June this year reached 1.396
billion dollars, increasing by 840 million dollars from 556
million dollars in the corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Some 1.714 million tourists had visited Egypt by the end of
June this year compared to 1.299 million of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
