<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Meets with Egyptian Foreign Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
met with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa here today for talks
on the future of the Palestinian-Israeli talks in the light of
recent developments in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Their talks dealt with Israel's decision to resume expansion of
Jewish settlements in the Palestinian territories of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip, a move which Egypt regards as an obstacle and grave
danger to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who presided over a two-day meeting of the Central
Committee of the PLO's mainstream Fatah Movement in Cairo, left
here today for Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Arafat met with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak here Saturday
amid the latest flurry of summits between Arab leaders with an
aim of reviving the stalled regional peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah meeting, which concluded today, mainly discussed a
number of issues related to Palestinian-Israeli negotiations,
including Israel's settlement policy and failure to withdraw its
troops from Hebron, the last West Bank town still under Israeli
occupation.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, which opened Saturday night, the committee
members also discussed domestic issues of the Palestinian
self-rule areas.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was held in Cairo to enable some committee members
who live outside the Palestinian self-rule areas to attend.
</P>
</TEXT>
