<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence Marred Peaceful Weekend Marches in N. Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Rioting Catholic youths attacked
police in Londonderry early today marring an otherwise peaceful
weekend of sectarian marches across Northern Ireland, reports from
Londonderry said.
</P>
<P>
About a hundred people, many wearing masks, threw petrol bombs
and rocks at police who had blocked off the central square for a
parade by Protestant Apprentice Boys.
</P>
<P>
Police fired plastic bullets and drove the youths back. They
said three police officers were injured and 15 people arrested
during the violence.
</P>
<P>
None of the incidents was serious, but they tarnished a sense
of relief over negotiations that allowed a Protestant Apprentice
Boys parade to pass quietly through the streets of Londonderry on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Many people feared that disturbances would erupt during the
march, after police attempts to block a Protestant parade last
month provoked the worst riots for years in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
But, after days of cool-headed negotiations, the Apprentice
Boys backed down from a confrontation over whether they could
parade along the city's walls.
</P>
<P>
Catholics living near the city walls, who had protested against
the march as a triumphalist show of Protestant dominance, called
off a counter-demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Seamus Hegarty, the Catholic bishop of Londonderry, said "what
happened last night was not representative." "Yesterday,
processions all over the city went off very well thanks to the
very considerable work of people on both sides," he added.
</P>
<P>
The bishop said he thought "drinking had been involved" and the
incident should not overshadow the earlier victories of reason
over hatred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
