<HEADLINE> Tanzania To Ensure Effective Sanctions On Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Prime Minister
Frederick Sumaye said here today that his government would ensure
that sanctions imposed on the Burundi military regime are
effective.
</P>
<P>
Frederick Sumaye told Canadian High Commissioner to Tanzania,
Mrs. Verona Edelstein that Tanzania was closely monitoring events
in Burundi after the imposition of economic sanctions against
Burundi by the East and Central African states on July 31.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government demanded an early restoration of the
national assembly and a lift of ban on politics in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
"We want the democratization process to start immediately," he
stressed, adding that Tanzania was happy with the positive
responses from the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
So far, five countries including Tanzania, Uganda, Kenya,
Rwanda and Ethiopia, have imposed sanctions on Burundi.
</P>
<P>
In reply, Edelstein said Canada supported the Arusha
Declaration on Burundi made by leaders of the East and Central
African sub-region.
</P>
<P>
"Canada stands ready to support reconstruction in Burundi.
However, there must be stability and peace for this effort to
succeed." said the Canadian high commissioner.
</P>
<P>
"The first step is negotiation. And we join the sub-regional
leaders that peace talks should take place immediately," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The Tutsi soldiers, headed by former military leader Major
Pierre Buyoya, ousted President Sylvestre Ntibantunganya in a
coup in late July. And the East African countries responded by
deciding to impose economic sanctions on the Burundi military
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
