<HEADLINE> Syria's Tourism Industry Develops Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Syria's tourism industry
developed rapidly over the past few years due to its numerous
tourist attractions and the government's tourist-oriented policy.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists to Syria jumped to 2.25 million in 1995
from 500,000 in 1990. The industry earned 50 million Syrian pounds
(about one million U.S. dollars) last year, said Syrian Minister
of Tourism Danhow Daoud today at a symposium.
</P>
<P>
Syrian tourism officials estimated that the number of tourists
will reach 4 million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Syria has famous archeological sites, summer resorts and up to
180 kilometers of sea shores. Its innumerable swimming beaches,
which are distinguished for their soft sand and surrounding green
hills, attract large numbers of tourists every year, especially
during the spring and summer seasons.
</P>
<P>
Damascus, the capital of Syria, has been listed as one of the
world's sanctuaries by the United Nations Educational, Scientific
and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to promote the development of tourism industry, the
Syrian government will further give top priority to tourist
projects and will encourage investments by the private sector,
said the minister.  
</P>
</TEXT>
