<HEADLINE> Sporadic Shooting in Monrovia Causes Pandemonium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Sporadic shooting in the Liberian
capital of Monrovia caused pandemonium among thousands of
residents who ran helter-skelter in search of refuge anywhere in
the city, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The shooting started about 6:00 p.m. on Saturday on Clay
Street and Camp Johnson Road and later spread to surrounding
areas near the Barclay training center, the downtown military
barracks where most Krahn militiamen reside, a witness said
today, quoted by the report.
</P>
<P>
The witness said ''Most residents packed up a few belongings,
including mattresses and food items, and fled towards the
diplomatic enclave of Mamba Point as the shooting intensified for
about one hour before the west African peacekeeping force, known
as ECOMOG, brought the situation under control.''
</P>
<P>
Heavily armed ECOMOG troops backed by tanks quelled the
situation and advised remaining residents in the area not to
leave, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the shooting incident followed
fisticuffs between relatives of two Krahn generals over a looted
mattress claimed by both groups.
</P>
<P>
''They then took up traditional weapons, including machetes,
wounding several persons," the report quoted a witness as
saying.
</P>
<P>
General Philip Kamah, Liberia's Deputy Armed Forces Chief of
Staff, was reported as saying today that the incident was a
result of a quarrel between two residents on Clay Street.
</P>
<P>
He dismissed as ''false'' rumours that Krahn militias wanted a
fresh round of fighting in the capital, which was devastated by
factional fighting that broke out in April.
</P>
<P>
The factions involved in the fighting have promised to stop
hostilities and start disarmament, according to a press statement
signed on July 31 by Liberia's transitional government in Abuja,
capital of Nigeria, shortly after the summit of the Economic
Community of West African States.
</P>
<P>
Monrovia has since remained calm at large.  
</P>
</TEXT>
