<HEADLINE> Iran, Turkey to Boost Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- The bilateral trade between
Turkey and Iran will reach 2.5 billion U.S. dollars annually,
Akbar Torkan, Iranian Road and Transportation Minister, said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Turkey have formed four sub-committees to boost
cooperation in the fields of energy, transportation, trade and
industry, Torkan, who is also the head of Iran-Turkey Joint
Commission, was quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
Iran will trade gas for electricity with Turkey in line with
agreements to be signed here Monday during Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan's visit, according to the minister. The Turkish
premier arrived here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Torkan said that the two countries had agreed to put the
Tarabuzan port at the disposal of Iran so that it could
facilitate the export to the world and the Central Asian Republics
through Iranian businessmen.
</P>
<P>
He said that visiting Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan
had also agreed on the construction of a railroad network and
early resumption of flights between Istanbul and Tabriz. 
