<HEADLINE> Iran Urges Turkey to Cut Relations with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Supreme Leader Ayatollah
Ali Khamenei today called on Turkey to sever its relations with
Israel but failed to obtain a clear response from the visiting
Turkish prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei made the direct call to Turkish Prime Minister
Necmettin Erbakan during a 50-minute meeting between the two
leaders in Tehran this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei was quoted by the state-run television IRIB as saying
"The Zionist regime is a very dangerous entity."
</P>
<P>
"It must be recognized that Israel will easily trample
anything when its interests are necessitated," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He told Erbakan: "We are hopeful that your country will
relinquish itself from the recent relationship with Israel at the
earliest opportune moment."
</P>
<P>
However, the pro-Islamic Turkish prime minister shied away from
a definite response, only saying "Turkey and Iran should expand
their ties in all fields in view of their particularities and
potentialities."
</P>
<P>
"Ankara is determined to expand its ties with Iran in all
fields," he added.
</P>
<P>
"I try to establish model relationship, with Iran, which will
be followed by other countries," Erbakan added.
</P>
<P>
Khamenei's statement reflected Iran's strong opposition to the
military cooperation between Turkey and Israel. Tehran hoped
Ankara would cancel its military agreement with Israel, which was
signed in February this year.
</P>
<P>
Iran's situation is rather delicate as the United States has
decided to step up sanctions against Tehran and Tripoli, Libya, on
charges of backing terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan arrived here Saturday afternoon at the invitation of
Iran's First Vice-President Hassan Habibi. He is accompanies by
250 government officials and businessmen, including Defense
Minister Turhan Tayan, Energy Minister Recai Kutan and
Environment Minister Ziyaettin Tokar.
</P>
<P>
Tehran is the first leg of Erbakan's 10-day foreign trip which
will also take him to Pakistan, Singapore, Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Top on the agenda for his trip to Tehran is to sign a 20
billion U.S. dollar gas deal with Iran and to solve border
security problems between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the future ties and cooperation with Turkey,
Khamenei said: "The two countries have massive possibilities
and potentiality for expanding and deepening relations."
</P>
<P>
He expressed his hope that the agreements between the two
governments to be signed Monday would quickly and seriously be
implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
