<HEADLINE> Afghan Delegation's Visit to Help Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The visit of a Afghan
government delegation led by Interior Minister Younas Qanooni to
Pakistan will help improve relations between the two countries,
the official Kabul Radio said today.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Kabul quoted the official broadcast as saying, "it
can be hoped that good intentions of both sides will evaporate the
atmosphere of mistrust and pave the way for the establishment of
good relations between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
A four-member Afghan government delegation arrived here
Saturday to hold talks with top Pakistani officials on bilateral
ties and supply of petroleum and food stuff from Pakistan to
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The radio said the three-day visit of the delegation will have
"far-reaching consequences and will open a new chapter in
relations between the two neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
Afghan-Pak ties hit rock bottom since the Pakistani embassy in
Kabul was burnt down last September. One staff member of the
embassy was killed while all diplomats in the embassy sustained
injuries in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan blamed the Kabul government for not providing adequate
protection to the embassy.
</P>
<P>
Kabul radio said Kabul wants to have good relations with all
countries especially its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
It said, "we believe by bringing consensus in the region, we
can promote cooperation and stability in the region."
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of the talks, the two government issued a
joint communique here today, saying the Pakistani government will
reopen its embassy in Kabul.
</P>
<P>
During their stay in the Pakistani capital, the Afghan
delegation held talks with President Farooq Leghari, Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto, Foreign Minister Aseff Ahmed Ali,
Interior Minister Nasirullah Babar and other Pakistani officials.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
