<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Pledges to Advance Peace Process with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu said here today that he wants to move forward
with an idea of activating the joint Israeli-Palestinian Joint
Committees to resolve the pending issues.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu made the remarks when he was addressing a press
conference held exclusively for Palestinian journalists, according
to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu failed to detail how to deal with the
delayed redeployment from Hebron and suspended final stage
negotiations with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He insisted in an interview with Al-Quds, an east
Jerusalem-based Palestinian Arabic-language newspaper, which
published Sunday that the time has not come yet for him to
consider meeting with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Hebron redeployment, the premier said that it
was passed down to him from his predecessor Shimon Peres who,
according to him, did not want to carry out the redeployment from
Hebron due to the escalations of Islamic extremist attacks and
fear for more bombing explosions that may take place during the
May 29 elections.
</P>
<P>
He added that he is studying the situation in order to find a
solution before the situation "explodes in our face."
</P>
<P>
On the issue of settlement expansion, Netanyahu claimed that
Oslo 2 accord did not freeze settlement activity and it has
stipulated the building of bypass roads. He said that the
government has not yet decided on what to do with the settlements
and the roads.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, the hardline Likud government of Netanyahu
decided to lift the freeze on expansion of Jewish settlements in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip, which was imposed by the former
Israeli Labor government that signed the Oslo 2 accord to pave the
way for peace talks with the Palestinians in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Interior Minister Eli Suissa today announced he
would grant 5 million U.S. dollars to Jewish settlements to help
them pay for the higher expenses.
</P>
<P>
Suissa told settlers while he toured the West Bank settlements
that they deserved the money because they had higher expenses as a
result of the Israeli-Palestinian self-rule agreements.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that all government ministers would
follow his footsteps and each minister would offer 5 million
dollars to the settlers.
</P>
<P>
Under the Oslo Accords, "neither side shall initiate or take
any step that will change the status of the West Bank and Gaza
Strip pending the outcome of the permanent status negotiations,"
the JMCC report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
