<HEADLINE> Sunken French Trawler's Boss Loses 7 Family Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Loic Riou, boss of the trawler
Essor which sank Sunday off the western coast of France, has lost
seven of his family members.
</P>
<P>
Agence France Presse quoted local officials in La Rochelle
facing the Island of Oleron as saying that among the dead were two
daughters of Riou's.
</P>
<P>
At least five people were drowned and four missing after Essor
sank two kilometers off the Island of Oleron in a festival held
each year to collect fund for the families of sea accidents. More
than 50 people were on board the trawler when it sank.
</P>
<P>
Two different versions of cause for the sinking has been given
by witnesses. Some of them said that the wreckage was caused by a
ground swell, while some others said it was due to an overloading
of passengers.
</P>
<P>
A seaman calling himself Eric said that the boat was attacked
by a ground swell from behind.
</P>
<P>
But a fishwoman said that the boat was carrying 24 more people
than is allowed by law on maritime businesses. She said that when
sprays of flowers were thrown into the sea to mark the dead of the
sea, all people were gathering on one side of the trawler to
watch, making the ship lose balance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
