<HEADLINE> Nepal's Ruling Party Expels Dissident Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's main ruling party the
Nepali Congress (NC) has expelled a dissident member due to his
activities against the party.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the NC central office here said
Jagannath Acharya, a former minister, has been involved recently
in anti-party activities in a bid to form a separate party.
</P>
<P>
It said that Acharya declared his intention to open a new
political party while addressing a meeting last week in Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
Acharya said at the meeting of the so-called social democratic
group, a group of dissident NC members, last Friday that a new
party must be formed to replace the NC which he said is now mired
in a race for power.
</P>
<P>
The dissident group, led by Acharya, is known for its voice
against NC President Girija Prasad Koirala and his policy. The
group has vowed to establish a new party to "restore social
democracy" in Nepal.  
