<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Target For Assets Appraising Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China has drawn a blueprint to
standardize the country's assets appraising industry over the next
15 years, according to an official of the State Administration of
State Property (SASP).
</P>
<P>
Zhang Youcai, director of the SASP, said at a recent national
conference on the sector that China is working to create a
legal system for assets appraisal in order to establish an
independent and impartial appraisal service industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that the country is revising the Appraisal Rules of
the State Property issued in 1991, part of which has become
"outmoded" for the present appraising service.
</P>
<P>
The country has also started drafting a set of regulations
governing the registration of the country's property appraisers,
whereby only certified public valuers (CPV) will be allowed to
do assets appraisal.
</P>
<P>
Annual exams will be held to decide who is qualified for the
appraisal service, Zhang added, and the SASP will improve its
supervision of the evaluation agencies.
</P>
<P>
Specialists here said that the effort to professionalize public
valuers indicates that China's assets evaluation methods are
approaching international standards, and thus there will be less
danger of losses of state property. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
