<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Plants More Cotton This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Egypt, which aspires to regain its
traditional domination of the world market for long-staple cotton,
increased its cotton-growing areas this year.
</P>
<P>
Egypt planted 920,000 feddans (386,400 hectares) of cotton
crop this year, an increase of 200,000 feddans over last year, an
Egyptian English-language newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The figures are a little bit different from those carried by
the newspaper last month.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian Gazette said in a report last month that the
cotton-growing areas increased to nearly 1 million acres
(404,858 hectares) this year from 720,000 acres (291,498 hectares)
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The paper today quoted Egyptian Minister of Agriculture Youssef
Wali as saying that this increase is due to government's new
policies to encourage farmers to plant cotton, one of the main
sources of Egypt's foreign currency income.
</P>
<P>
These policies include fixing a higher minimum price for
purchasing cotton from farmers and opening up the cotton trade.
</P>
<P>
With a good harvest in sight and liberalization of cotton
exports and imports, Egypt expects to regain its traditional
domination of the world market for long-staple cotton in the
1996-97 marketing year.
</P>
<P>
According to the new policies, the paper said, private and
cooperative companies as well as individuals can purchase cotton
directly from farmers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the paper added, the government guarantees a minimum
price for cotton if farmers cannot find a purchaser at a better
price, and cotton growers will be able to offer their crops to the
marketing units affiliated to the Main Bank for Agriculture Credit
and Development.
</P>
<P>
The new policies also allow the export of cotton in any
quantity during the marketing season, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
For years, the government has diverted much valuable
long-staple cotton to the domestic textile industry instead of
exporting it and importing cheaper varieties in its place.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has only imported cotton from California and Arizona in
the United States, on the grounds that cotton from other areas may
carry dangerous pests and diseases.
</P>
<P>
It was reported earlier that the government has allowed the
import of short-staple cotton from Syria this year, and that Egypt
has also been considering importing cotton from Australia, Turkey,
Uzbekistan and other areas of the United States except California
and Arizona. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
