<HEADLINE> Efforts Urged to Enhance Teaching Foreigners Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- China will strengthen efforts in
teaching foreigners Chinese language in the next few years, a top
official in education sector said here today.
</P>
<P>
Minister in charge of the State Educational Commission Zhu
Kaixuan made the remark at the closing ceremony of the Fifth
International Symposium on Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that since China initiated the policy of reform and
opening to the outside world, Sino-foreign contacts and exchanges
in economy, culture, science and technology have increased, and
there has been an increasing number of people in the world who
show great interest in learning Chinese language.
</P>
<P>
He called for good efficiency and success in teaching Chinese
as a foreign language in order to meet the demands of peoples from
all over the world.
</P>
<P>
The official also called for efforts to strengthen the work of
this newly-born discipline -- teaching Chinese as a foreign
language -- and improve the theoretical studies in the respect.
</P>
<P>
The symposium, which opened on August 8, is the biggest of the
kind. More than 400 professors and scholars from 27 countries and
regions around the world took part in discussions on linguistical
theories, the Chinese language and culture, transcultural
intercourse, Chinese textbooks, the computer-aided Chinese
language teaching and test for Chinese proficiency.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Yongkui, standing vice-director of the office of the State
Leading Group for Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language, said
that the symposium opened under the situation of "intense popular
interest" in China and "Chinese craze" throughout the world. All
participants have expressed a common wish: the world need all the
more the Chinese language, and full play should be given to the
work of teaching Chinese as a foreign language, he added.
</P>
<P>
At the symposium, the newly-elected International Society for
Chinese Teaching decided that the next international symposium on
teaching Chinese will be held in Germany or China in 1999. enditem
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
