<HEADLINE> Russian Security Chief, Top Chechen Separatist Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian security chief Alexander
Lebed today held "constructive" talks with a Chechen separatist
commander, lifting hopes of peace in warn-torn Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Lebed and Chechen separatist chief of staff Aslan Maskhadov
discussed a cease-fire and separatist troop withdrawals from the
Chechen capital Grozny, Russia's Security Council press service
said.
</P>
<P>
Despite the first high-level meeting between Moscow and the
rebels since the separatists stormed into Grozny last Tuesday,
battles continued in the city which a Russian official said was
still controlled by the Chechen guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Russian military officials said that 169 of the 7,000 Russian
soldiers stationed in the republic had been killed, 618 had been
wounded and several hundred were missing.
</P>
<P>
Lebed, named on Saturday as President Boris Yeltsin's personal
envoy in Chechnya, arrived in a Chechen village 20 kilometers
south of Grozny for the talks with Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
His car came under fire twice on the way to the talks, but no
one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
The press service of the Security Council, of which Lebed is
chief, indicated that the shots could have been "friendly fire" as
his late-night arrival had puzzled several Russian checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
Lebed's first trip to Chechnya since being appointed security
chief in June seems to indicate he is taking a leading role in
trying to settle the 20-month crisis. He was back in Moscow by
midday on Monday and immediately briefed Yeltsin on the talks.
</P>
<P>
Chechen separatist fighters stormed Grozny last Tuesday in an
attempt to win control of the city from the Russian army. Refugees
have been fleeing Grozny since last week, and rebels were laying
mines and preparing defensive positions in the capital against
Russian attacks.
</P>
<P>
A representative from the Russian military command was quoted
by the Interfax news agency as saying that the separatists now
controlled a large part of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The conflict in Chechnya has been going on since December 1994,
when President Yeltsin sent in troops to crush the growing
independence movement in the republic.
</P>
<P>
Russian leaders have ruled out separatists' demand for full
independence for Chechnya. However, they agreed on Sunday to take
radical measures, possibly including declaring a state of
emergency, to settle the conflict.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said troops in Chechnya had
to be strengthened, but did not make it clear whether this meant
reinforcements would be sent in.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
