<HEADLINE> DPRK Returns Body of Drowned South Korean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) today returned to South Korea the body of a
drowned South Korean man, found in the sea near the DPRK's western
border.
</P>
<P>
The handover of the body, identified as Kang Tae-hui, was
proposed by Pyongyang last week and took place through the Red
Cross at the truce village of Panmunjom, the normal border meeting
place for the two sides.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time in eight months that the DPRK has
returned the bodies of South Koreans. Pyongyang repatriated the
remains of three South Korean fishermen in December last year.
</P>
<P>
Last week, South Korea returned to the DPRK the bodies of four
drowned DPRK persons including two soldiers swept into southern
sector of the border by flooded rivers.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of the successful efforts by the DPRK and South
Korean Red Cross branches to repatriate the bodies of drowned
victims, Kang Young-hoon, head of the South Korean Red Cross, has
proposed a meeting with his DPRK counterpart to discuss food aid
and the reunification of divided families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
