<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese Language to Spread Worldwide (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The study of the Chinese
language is experiencing the greatest revival in its long history,
and its popularity is increasing throughout the world, according
to scholars who attended the Fifth International Symposium on
Teaching Chinese as a Foreign Language, which closed today in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Over 400 scholars and experts in the field from 27 countries
and regions attended the event. This was the gathering's record
attendance.
</P>
<P>
An official from the organization committee said that these
participants are the guiding force behind the promotion of
teaching Chinese as a foreign language.
</P>
<P>
Scholars at the symposium said the number of people who are
studying Chinese throughout the world has increased rapidly in the
past five years; nearly one million Japanese and 500,000 Koreans
study the ancient language.
</P>
<P>
Chinese is becoming a popular field of study both in countries
that use Chinese characters as a writing style and those that
don't, thanks to China's booming economic development and its
increase in cooperation and exchange with other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
About 500 universities in the United States have offered
Chinese courses in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Experts agree that by the 21st century, Chinese will be one of
the most popular languages in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Chinese Language to Spread Worldwide (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The focus of discussion at the symposium was how to promote
teaching Chinese as a foreign language in the world. Scholars
agreed that on one hand, the Chinese government should take
greater responsibility to publish high-level teaching materials,
establish an advanced academic system, train more qualified
teachers, and popularize the Chinese Proficiency Test -- Hanyu
Shuiping Kaoshi (HSK).
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the International Society for Chinese
Teaching should urge its membership countries or regions to
promote teaching Chinese.
</P>
<P>
New ideas about the relation between culture and language have
attracted the attention of many of the scholars, who believe that
the function of Chinese should be simple communication instead of
complex research.
</P>
<P>
They also suggested that knowledge about traditional Chinese
culture and the recent changes in the economy and society be added
to Chinese teaching, in addition to language skills and grammar
study.
</P>
<P>
The experts also discussed the effects of modern technology on
Chinese teaching. Electronic techniques and computers have speeded
up Chinese teaching methods, they said.
</P>
<P>
Reforms in the teaching system and the use of computers for
learning Chinese created a great deal of interest among the
experts.
</P>
<P>
The scholars also discussed ways to improve the teaching
methods in countries that have diversified cultural backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
The study of Chinese plays an important role in connecting
overseas Chinese people with their motherland, said the scholars
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Foreigners of the Chinese origin should pay more attention to
teaching Chinese to their children who are growing up in foreign
countries, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
