<HEADLINE> Indian Court Stays Criminal Proceedings Against Rao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 ( Xinhua ) -- India's Supreme Court today
stayed criminal proceedings initiated by Delhi Chief Metropolitan
Magistrate, Prem Kumar, against former prime minister P.V.
Narasimha Rao in the L. Pathak cheating case of 100,000 US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The stay on the proceedings came close on the heels of an
earlier order of the Supreme Court staying the operation of
summons issued by the lower court directing Rao to personally
appear before the court on August 2.
</P>
<P>
In a brief order in the apex court, the judges said that it
appeared proper to them that the matter be heard for final
disposal on August 20 and 21. They directed that no further
proceedings should be taken against Rao by the chief metropolitan
magistrate as per his order dated July 9.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Rao moved a petition before the Supreme
Court on July 30 challenging the Delhi high court verdict
upholding an order of the chief metropolitan magistrate summoning
him to appear as co-accused in the cheating case.
</P>
<P>
UK-based businessman L. Pathak had said before the lower court
that he gave 100,000 dollars to Indian godman Chandraswami and his
associate to secure contacts for the supply of newsprint and paper
pulp to India on the assurance of Rao, who was the then foreign
minister, but Rao denied that he had anything to do with the case.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
