<HEADLINE> French Police Evacuate African Hunger Strikers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, August 12 (Xinhua) -- French police forcibly evacuated
10 African hunger strikers and two pregnant African women at dawn
today from the Paris church they've been occupying for over a
month.
</P>
<P>
Some 300 police stormed the church at 5.50 a.m. local time
(0350 GMT) and carted the hunger strikers away on stretchers, the
Agence France Presse news agency quoted a doctor working for
humanitarian group Medecin du Monde as saying.
</P>
<P>
The police were accompanied by doctors with medical equipment,
a spokesman for the Paris police said.
</P>
<P>
A police communique denied the raid was aimed at evacuating the
Africans from the Saint Bernard Church. It said the operation was
undertaken on health grounds to protect the lives of those on
hunger strike.
</P>
<P>
The hunger strikers, along with some 300 other African
immigrants, had been holed up in the Saint Bernard church for 39
days in protest at the French government's immigration policy and
regulations. They face deportation under legislation passed in
1993.
</P>
<P>
The were demanding the government impose a moratorium on
deportations and issue them with residency papers. 
</P>
