<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Al-Hariri announced here today that he would run for the upcoming
parliamentary election to win one of the six Sunnit seats for the
Beirut constituency in the half-Moslem-half-Christian unicameral
House.
</P>
<P>
Hariri made public his position at the last moment after a
myriad of conflicting speculations by local media in the last
several months and even this morning on the overweight prime
minister's participation.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference in his Beirut residence at noon today,
Hariri said that he decided to join the election race, giving up
a previous decision of neutrally staying away from the election,
which was announced in May.
</P>
<P>
"About one month ago, I was asked by reporters about my
decision on participation in the elections, I promised to
announce my decision by August 12," the Sunnit prime minister
said.
</P>
<P>
"I'm now in front of you to announce that I am to be a
candidate in the parliamentary election in Beirut city," he
said. His remarks caused a warm applause in the hall.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the decision was aimed at "keeping a unity of
Beirut."
</P>
<P>
"Throughout the past few years, I have been working in order
to consolidate the people's safety, to close the page of past
pains and to enable the political system to work effectively by
building the country into an institution desirously hoped by the
people," the prime minister underlined.
</P>
<P>
"Our hope continuously remains on the Arab and international
levels for a liberation of our occupied lands in the south and
western Beqaa, an implementation of U.N. Resolution 425 and an
Israeli withdrawal to the internationally-recognized border,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his country's adherence to a coordination with
Syria, with which "we are working together for just, comprehensive
and lasting peace."
</P>
<P>
Hariri declined to specify the list of his allied candidates,
with whom he would form a coalition for the election campaign.
</P>
