<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Media to Refrain from Showing Bias Against Laos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Thai media representatives at a
seminar agreed to exercise self-restraint in what could be
interpreted as a "racial and cultural bias" against Laos.
</P>
<P>
The one-day seminar, held on Saturday in Udon Thani,
northeastern Thailand, was the first of its kind the Thai Foreign
Ministry has called to discuss the media's role in promoting
Thai-Lao relations, according to the Nation newspaper today.
</P>
<P>
The seminar recommended that a list of words and expressions,
deemed improper by Laotians and should therefore be avoided, be
prepared for circulation among the Thai media.
</P>
<P>
The Thai and Laotian languages are similar and Laotians can
easily receive and understand Thai television and radio programs.
</P>
<P>
It was suggested that the term "baan pee muang nong" (elder-
brother-and-younger-brother relations), which the Thais often use
to describe close Thai-Lao ties, should be avoided, as it can be
interpreted as Thailand being the elder brother while Laos being
the younger brother.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the seminar, Thai ambassador to Laos Somphan
Kokilanond said Lao leaders were also disturbed by negative press
reports in the Thai media and articles containing improper
expressions about Laos.
</P>
<P>
The seminar explored the intent of Thai media in reporting
about Laos as well as the impact of negative reporting and Thai
television and radio programs on Laotian society.
</P>
<P>
Media representatives at the seminar generally acknowledged
that Thai press reports were not prepared with the intention of
damaging bilateral relations or of denigrating Laos, but they
agreed that they should try to avoid being biased towards Laos.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
