<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Announces to Run for  Parliamentary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hariri's two principle Sunnit rivals in Beirut, Deputy and
former Prime Minister Salim Al-Hoss and candidate Tammam Salam,
have their respective popular bases in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese will choose 128 new members of the parliament in
the protracted election, which is to be held on the successive
five Sundays beginning from August 18 in the country's five
governorates.
</P>
<P>
The four-year term of the present parliament expires on
October, 15.
</P>
<P>
Even before the polling starts, a series of dramatic or
violent events have been witnessed in this country, whose
estimated population of three million is made up of 17 Christian
and Moslem sectarian communities.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Constitutional Council, the country's supreme
justice authority, ruled against the election law passed by the
parliament last month, on the grounds that the law allows
discriminations among the citizens, candidates and constituencies.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary administration and justice committee are to
meet later today to consider revisions of the controversial
election law presented by the government in line with the
Constitutional Council's verdict.
</P>
<P>
The debate is expected to provide an indication as to how the
full session of parliament Tuesday will go amid reports that
opposition members of the parliament were already looking for
loopholes in the revisions.
</P>
<P>
Beirut's conservative daily An-Nahar reported today that
a brief clash with firearms took place in the mainly Druze
district of Aley, Mount Lebanon, between supporters of rival
Druze leaders Walid Jumblat, a minister in Hariri's government,
and Deputy Talal Arslan.
</P>
<P>
Arslan's followers said that members of Jumblat's Progressive
Socialist Party (PSP) opened fire at Arslan's convoy when it was
passing through Aghmid village.
</P>
<P>
But a statement issued by PSP accused Arslan's supporters of
opening fire first.
</P>
<P>
Similar shooting incidents were reported in eastern and
northern Lebanon over hanging up and tearing down pictures of rival
candidates. 
</P>
