<HEADLINE> Russian Police Confirm Terrorist Bomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Russian police say a bomb blast at
a railway station in southern Russia this morning was the work of
terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Eight people were injured, four seriously, when the bomb
exploded on a crowded passenger train as it pulled out of Trubnaya
Station, about 15 kilometers from the city of Volgograd, at 5.15
a.m. (0115 GMT), ITAR-TASS News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Most passengers escaped injury as the train didn't overturn
after the explosion, police said.
</P>
<P>
Following preliminary investigations, police said the explosive
device was planted under one of the carriages of train 606 which
was travelling from the town of Astrakhan to Volgograd.
</P>
<P>
This was the third bomb exploded or be planted on the railway
line in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
Police said the latest bomb might be planted by the same
terrorists who detonated a bomb on an empty carriage of train 606
at Volgograd station on July 25. There were no injuries in that
explosion.
</P>
<P>
Investigators believe the terrorists responsible for the two
blasts apparently wanted to "correct their previous mistakes" in the
second operation.
</P>
<P>
Russia's huge public transport network has suffered a string of
mysterious bomb explosions over the last few months, three of
which happened in Moscow in June and July.
</P>
<P>
Four people were killed in a blast on the Moscow underground on
June 12 and more than 30 people were hurt in two bomb explosions
on trolley buses last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
