<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 12:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Join Hands in Fighting PKK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Turkey announced here
today that they have joined hands in fighting the Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK), an anti-Turkish government group, thereby settling
the thorny issue that had for years strained the relations
between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The visiting Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan stressed
at a two-hour press conference, held in former royal Sadabad
Palace, that the border regions must remain peaceful and
tranquil.
</P>
<P>
While stressing the need to maintain regional security, he
said that Turkey is willing to cooperate with Iran to uproot
terrorist activities throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
"Our cooperation in this respect will be important bilaterally,
regionally and internationally," he said.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan emphasized that Turkey and Iran are working on the
elimination of terrorism in the region. But he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources told Xinhua that Turkey has obtained the
assurance from the Iranian side that Tehran will keep silent
over any Turkish military operation against the PKK in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish security authorities also agreed to compensate for
those who had been killed or injured in the recent border
incidents due to rocketing attacks by Turkish helicopters.
</P>
<P>
Iran's First Vice-President Hassan Habibi said at the press
conference that "Our borders have been peaceful in the past and
they must be peaceful in the future."
</P>
<P>
"We must make sure that people living there should not be
bothered and joint actions should be taken to stop terrorism
there," he added. "We have reached agreement on the necessity of
maintaining and respecting the territorial integrity of Iraq
together with stopping terrorism there."
</P>
<P>
Observers here said that means Turkey, Iran and even Iraq will
join hands to launch military operation against PKK. In return,
the Turkish security authorities will also help Iran fight
against anti-government elements belonging to the People's
Mojaheedin of Iran, who reside in Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the settlement of border security
issue is another major achievement during Turkish Prime Minister
Erbakan's visit here.
</P>
<P>
Turkey signed today a 20-billion U.S. dollar deal for Iranian
natural gas exports over s pan of 22 years beginning from 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, the Turkish prime minister
is planning a four-way summit together with the leaders of Iran,
Iraq and Syria on the situation in northern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan believes that the problem in northern Iraq should
be solved through joint efforts by the region's countries,
namely, Turkey, Iran, Iraq and Syria.
</P>
<P>
The Kurdish population is estimated at more than 20 million,
concentrated mainly near the borders of Turkey, Iraq, Iran and
Syria. Kurdish attempts at breaking away or gaining autonomy have
been suppressed violently by the governments of these countries.
</P>
<P>
The PKK is fighting for autonomy for Turkey's 12 million Kurds,
who comprise one-fifth of the population. More than 21,000 people
have been killed in the clashes between the PKK and the Turkish
government troops since 1984.
</P>
<P>
Today's English-language daily Tehran Times, which has a
strong background of the Iranian Foreign Ministry, published an
editorial voicing welcome to Erbakan's efforts.
</P>
<P>
"Countries concerned should try their utmost to materialize
the idea. The four-way summit will be in the interests of the
participating states," the daily said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
