<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Mt. Merapi Spews More Fumes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Mountain Merapi in Central Java,
1,200 kilometers east of Jakarta, this morning started to emit
thick fumes after a day of calm, said an official of the
Volcanology Directorate Office in Yogjakarta, 30 kilometer south
of the volcano.
</P>
<P>
But the fumes emitted were relatively small in volume and were
spewed only 400 meters away from the crater, Antara news agency
quoted the official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lava was however seen flowing to the West from the volcano's
crater, down to Krasak river.
</P>
<P>
Officers at the Kaliurang and Babadan monitoring posts reported
that they found difficulties in observing the flow of lava and
fumes because of thick smoke. "But we could hear thundering
sounds form the volcano."
</P>
<P>
The local authorities on Saturday have upgraded the volcano's
status from "alert" to "ready".
</P>
<P>
The Yogjakarta Volcanology Directorate Office has also issued a
warning to people living around the areas of Mt. Merapi to prepare
for evacuation if the situation worsens.
</P>
<P>
The 2,962-meter Merapi volcano increased its activities last
week. It was recorded to have spewed hot clouds and light-blazing
lava for 27 times which blacked the peak of the mountain.
</P>
<P>
The Merapi last erupted in November 1993, spewing hot lava,
raining volcanic ash for several kilometers, killing more than 60
people, injuring more than 100 and causing widespread property
damage.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia has the highest number of volcanoes in the world.
Among them, 500 are located along the "ring of fire", 127 active
and 65 listed as "dangerous".  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
