<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Design Computing System for Visually Impaired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Polytechnic
University and the Hong Kong Society for the Blind have jointly
launched a large-scale research project to develop a Chinese
computing interface based on Cantonese braille for the visually
impaired in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the project said today that the project will
span two years for the development of a voice output mechanism and
an interface to support a Cantonese braille input and output
device.
</P>
<P>
He said that recent computer programs successfully developed in
the West have made the Windows graphical environment accessible to
the blind and the visually impaired, a similar mechanism to handle
Chinese on this popular computing platform is not yet available.
</P>
<P>
The new system, based on Microsoft Chinese Windows, will
provide real-time conversion between Cantonese braille and
standard Chinese characters. There will be an output mechanism to
support reading in Chinese braille, and the visually impaired can
make use of an ordinary keyboard to input Chinese characters via
the braille encoding scheme, he said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the system will provide a voice output mechanism
to indicate the location of the pointing device. When the mouse
pointer moves to a specific location on the screen, the computer
will voice out that function in Cantonese, thus customizing the
Chinese Windows environment for the visually impaired. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
