<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Ministry of Local Administration has earmarked
3.7 billion Egyptian pounds (about 1.09 billion U.S. dollars) to
develop Sinai for the current fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
According to today's Cairo Press Review, this sum will be
invested in a series of projects of housing, tourism, transport,
trade, petroleum, industry, agriculture, electricity, education,
health and other related services.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese Minister of Water and Electrical Resources
Elie Hobeika has asked the government to allocate 110 million
U.S. dollars for a project of decreasing air pollution from the
three major power stations in the country.
</P>
<P>
Today's Eco News business weekly said that investigations
conducted by the Lebanese Electricity Board (LEB) show that the
level of pollution resulted from the power stations is generally
higher than the approved standards in Europe.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese exports increased during the first half of
this year by 94 million U.S. dollars, or 26.4 percent, over the
same period last year, the Beirut Eco News business weekly
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the first six months reached 449 million dollars, as
against 355 million dollars for the same period in 1995, with the
monthly average jumping to 75 million dollars in 1996 from 69
million dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Imports also encouragingly dropped during the same period to
3,471 million dollars in 1996 from 3,540 million dollars in 1995,
a decline of 38 million dollars, or 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Turkey signed here today a 20 billion
U.S. dollar gas agreement despite U.S. threat to impose tough
sanctions on Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Based on the accord, Iran will export 4-10 billion cubic
meters of gas to Turkey for 22 years beginning from 1999. Iran
would be getting an annual profit of 1 billion dollars from the
gas sales. 
</P>
