<HEADLINE> True Religious Leaders Should Love Motherland: Living Buddha (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- A leading living Buddha urged the
Dalai Lama in exile today to learn from the late Panchen Lama to
love the motherland and carry forward the tradition and spirit
of Buddhism.
</P>
<P>
"Only those who love the country as well as the religion are
true religious leaders," said Agya Lobsangtudain Gyaurme Gyanco in
an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The 46-year-old living Buddha chairs the Gumbum (Taer)
Monastery in Northwest China's Qinghai Province, which is one of
the four most respected monasteries of the Yellow Sect of the
Tibetan Buddhism. The other three are located in Lhasa.
</P>
<P>
The late Panchen Lama, who died in 1989, was installed to his
holy throne in this monastery and spent nine years here. The Agya
Living Buddha has been learning Buddhism from the Panchen since he
arrived at the temple at an age of two.
</P>
<P>
"The Panchen's words and deeds of loving both the country and
religion has set himself an example for our monastery, and further
consolidated our belief in our whole Chinese nation and our
religion," the Agya said.
</P>
<P>
"He was the very true leader of Tibetan Buddhism," the Agya
said.
</P>
<P>
The Dalai Lama was once a religious leader in Tibet in addition
to the Panchen Lama. But he has so far been going in the other
direction, the Agya said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> True Religious Leaders Should Love Motherland: Living Buddha (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"It has been nearly 40 years since the 14th Dalai Lama left his
hometown. How can he turn to be a tool of a handful of separatists
and foreign anti-China forces?" he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he feels regret and deplores the Dalai's illegal
interference with the normal process of the reincarnation of the
late Panchen Lama and his recent deeds in Europe, both intended to
split Tibet from China, and internationalize the issue of Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The areas where Tibetans live, including parts of Qinghai, have
undergone drastic changes in the past 40 years, and the Tibetan
people are expecting more rapid economic development, better
living standards, unity among different nationalities and a stable
social environment, the Agya said.
</P>
<P>
"The Dalai Lama, living in exile for too long a time, would be
better coming back to have a look at the real situation, and his
old mind-set, in my opinion, should be changed, too," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Panchen Lama had taught the Agya in his early years that
"study hard when you are young and serve the country and
nationality in the future, you are carrying forward the spirit of
Buddhism," the living Buddha recalled.
</P>
<P>
When the late Panchen was imprisoned in Beijing or sent to
Gumbum Monastery for rehabilitation through labor during the
period of the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), he just took it as
an test for his pursuit of Buddhism, just as other difficulties as
illness and hunger, the Agya said.
</P>
<P>
The Panchen Lama once said that chanting scriptures in temples
all one's life does not necessarily lead to success in Buddhism,
but the strong willed, even under exterior pressures and
disturbances and with no conditions to pay due respects to the
Buddhas, can be more loyal in mind by having more contacts with
the society and enriching his life, the Agya recalled.
</P>
<P>
And the Panchen always believed the day will come when he would
be announced innocent, according to the Agya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
