<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man, 78, Builds Tibetan Village's First Highway - By Hand! </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- An old Tibetan man, who for many
years was a serf, is ensuring that his remote village has its
first highway - by building it himself.
</P>
<P>
The one-man road building enterprise is a labour of love for
78 years old Duojiciren.
</P>
<P>
His dream is even more ambitious - a road from his Tibetan
village to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
"Although we do not have a highway in our village now, we will
one day build a road directly to Beijing", says Duojiciren.
</P>
<P>
During the past fifteen years he spent most of his time
building a road for his village.
</P>
<P>
He lives in Quna village of Cuona county in Tibet. Located in
the middle part of the Himalaya mountains, the village is remote
and more than 4,000 meters above the sea level.
</P>
<P>
In the old days Duojiciren was a serf and he remembers very
clearly that it was the Chinese Communist Party that liberated him
and made him the master of his own life.
</P>
<P>
He retired in 1981 at the age of 61. Since he was still single,
the local government took the responsibility of supporting him
with food and clothes as well as health care and other articles
for daily use.
</P>
<P>
"My life is given by the people and I wanted to do something
for the people even after I retired", that is exactly what he
thought at that time.
</P>
<P>
So he picked up a shovel and started to build the road.
</P>
<P>
The shovel have been changed one after another, the road has
become longer, while he has become older.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen years has passed by and he is now a 78 year old man,
but his work is continuing.
</P>
<P>
"I am not far from death, but my neighbouring villagers will
get nearer and nearer to Beijing", he says.
</P>
<P>
For the old man, Beijing means a lot.
</P>
<P>
"It means hope, it means a modern life, it means our future,"
said the roadbuilder of Quna village. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
