<HEADLINE> Indonesian Security Authorities Arrest PRD Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian security
authorities have arrested Budiman Sudjatmiko, chairman of the
People's Democratic Party (PRD), which has been accused of
masterminding the July 27 riots, a high-ranking military officer
said here today.
</P>
<P>
Lt. Gen. Syarwan Hamid, chief of staff for socio-political
affairs of Indonesian Armed Forces disclosed that Budiman, 27, and
four other major activists of the party were arrested on Sunday in
Jabatabek, West Java.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, another officer Brig. Gen. Amir Syarifuddin said
that early this morning, four others of the PRD major activities
were also arrested in other places of West Java and some documents
they carried were also seized, he added.
</P>
<P>
The government has accused the PRD, a 1,000-member umbrella
group of worker, student and farmer organization, of slandering
the president and the government at a free speech forum outside
the headquarters of the Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI) last
month.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1995, the PRD has been blamed for many
anti-government protests and labor strikes last year. The
military has hunted Budiman and his followers since the July 27
riots in Jakarta which left three people died and more than 20
others injured.
</P>
<P>
The riots followed the takeover of the PDI headquarters by
supporters of PDI new leader Soerjadi from supporters of ousted
PDI leader Megawati Sukarnoputri, daughter of Indonesia's late
first president Sukarno.
</P>
<P>
The clashes destroyed and burned more than 22 buildings, 91
cars and two motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
According to the military, over 200 people have been detained
for questioning in connection with the riots.
</P>
<P>
Megawati, elected as PDI leader in 1993 to a five year term,
was also summoned last week for questioning.
</P>
<P>
A breakaway faction of PDI held a congress in June in Medan,
north Sumatra, installed Soerjadi as new party chairman but the
congress was strongly opposed by the supporters of Megawati.
</P>
</TEXT>
