<P>
Kang made the proposal at a press conference on the occasion
of the 25th anniversary of the KNRC's proposal for the inter-Korean
reunion of separated families.
</P>
<P>
"To resolve the problem of dispersed families, a South-North
(South Korea and the DPRK) meeting should be pursued despite
political and military problems," Kang said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the red cross organizations of the two sides should
hold a meeting as soon as possible involving their presidents or
vice presidents anywhere and without preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have numerous problems to deal with, including the
dispersed families issue and natural disaster relief efforts,
through mutual assistance based on humanitarian principles and
brotherhood, Kang noted.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, the KNRC has sent 1.48 million U.S. dollars
worth of flour, cooking oil and milk powder for flood victims in
the DPRK on seven occasions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
