<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discovering Martian Life Be Little Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Is there life on the planet Mars?
</P>
<P>
Just as officials of the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration of the United States (NASA) built up the dreams and
hopes of a generation of sci-fi fanatics hoping to meet little
green Martians, two German Scientists have brought the topic down
to earth.
</P>
<P>
They told a conference in Beijing that there is little hope of
detecting traces of organic life on Mars in near future.
</P>
<P>
The topic about Martian life is sweeping the world after NASA's
recent finding of organic compounds in a Martian meteorite.
</P>
<P>
Professor Gerlind Dreibus-Kapp and Heinrich Wanke of Max-Planck
Institute pointed out that Mars is a planet rich in volatiles, but
very poor in water, so any living thing would find it hard to lead
a life there, especially on the planet's surface.
</P>
<P>
According to evidence from the SNC meteorite, which fell from
Mars to Earth in ancient times, the water concentration in Martian
mantle is estimated to be 40 ppm, far less than the terrestrial
equivalents. Contrary to the low abundance of water, sulfur is
found in large concentration on the planet, widely existing in the
form of sulfur dioxide which is extruded from the depth of Martian
mantle by volcanic activity.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the mean surface temperature of Mars at low latitudes
is 55 centigrade degrees below zero, while at the poles it drops
to less than 144 centigrade degrees below zero, which is lower
than the freezing points of water and sulfur dioxide,
</P>
<P>
The two scientists said that on Mars, water is a solid at all
latitudes, carbon dioxide a solid or gas depending on latitude,
and sulfur dioxide a liquid or solid. Such an environment can not
meet the least heat consumption of a living primitive microbe.
</P>
<P>
The NASA Researchers announced on August 6 that they have
discovered evidence of ancient single-cell life on Mars in remains
of a meteorite that fell to Earth 13,000 years ago. Besides
triggering a Mars craze worldwide, the finding provided a new
evidence to the hypothesis that a boom of Martian lives emerged
under a warm climate two billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, Dreibus said that a greenhouse effect caused by the
exhalation of sulfur dioxide in large quantity could once have
turned the atmosphere hot on Mars, but the appearance of Martian
life forms was not the inevitable outcome of a warmer climate.
</P>
<P>
Before this, other several experts scoffed at NASA's claim and
said the evidence would have to be much stronger to be credible.
</P>
<P>
"The conclusion is at best premature and more probably wrong,"
said John Kerridge, a planetary scientist at the university of
California, San Diego, adding that the organic chemicals found in
the Martian meteorite are not an irrefutable evidence of life.
</P>
<P>
Although it is of little hope to find neighbors on Mars
immediately, people's curiosity for Martian life will be rekindled
as the US government announced to send an unmanned spacecraft to
Mars in 1997. The second US spaceship will be launched in 1998 and
reach Mars after ten months' flight.
</P>
<P>
Because of the rough conditions on Mars surface, any living
thing, if there should be, has to hide itself in the depth several
hundred meters from the surface, according to scientists.
</P>
<P>
But the in-depth drilling technology is still not available,
they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
