<HEADLINE> Australia To Join US in Exploring Life On Mars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian Science and
Technology Minister Peter McGauran expressed the country's
interest in joining hands with the United States to find life on
Mars.
</P>
<P>
In a news release, McGauran said that Australia would use its
deep space observation facilities to help the National
Aeronautical and Space Administration (NASA) of the US to make
"the momentous scientific discovery of this century."
</P>
<P>
He said that Australia had been an active participant in the
search for intelligent life beyond earth. Australia's Commonwealth
Scientific and Industrial Research Organization (CSIRO) is
involved in an extensive four-month search for extra-terrestrial
intelligence (SETI) program run by the US.
</P>
<P>
CSIRO's Parkes Radio Telescope and Tidbinbilla Space Tracking
Station have begun to participate in SETI programs since the first
of such program in the world was launched in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The Tidbinbilla Space Tracking Station near Canberra is one of
the three NASA deep space stations in the world. It is managed on
behalf of the NASA by the Australian Space Office. It is now
playing a key role in relaying radio signals from NASA's 1.5
billion-Australian-dollar (1.2 billion-US-dollar) Galileo
spacecraft that is exploring Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
"The finding of evidence by a group of NASA scientists that
life may have existed on Mars is being observed with keen interest
in Australia," he said.
</P>
<P>
CSIRO's involvement in previous SETI programs and the United
Nations Committee in charge of these issues were a proof of
Australia's ability to contribute to important international space
programs, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
