<HEADLINE> India's Polyester Industry in Shakeout </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 12 (Xinhua ) -- The Indian polyester industry
has been in shakeout in recent years due to cash crunch, dropping
prices and looming overcapacity, polyester industry sources said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Many small, unviable plants are either shutting down or
slashing production. Two companies, Prag Bosimi Synthetics and
Nirlon, have stopped production. Orkay, JCT, Haryana Petrochem
and Shree Synthetics are operating at low levels.
</P>
<P>
The closure takes away nearly 28,500 tons out of the market.
Prag Bosimi, a new plant with a capacity of 25,000 tons, could
never achieve full capacity utilization. In June last year, the
company produced only 51 tons. This year, it ran for three months
till March. The production last month was only 81 tons, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Nirlon, an old player which entered the business in 1970,
produced only 1,932 tons in 1994-95 when it had an installed
capacity of 3,500 tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
