<HEADLINE> Beijing's Banks See Marked Increase in Loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's banks witnessed a
marked increase in loans during the first half of the year, with
the total volume reaching 159.775 billion yuan, an increase of
10.444 billion yuan over the figure for the beginning of 1996.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents an increase of 15.63 percent when
compared with the same period of last year, according to "Beijing
Economic Information".
</P>
<P>
The paper says that most of the loans are short-term, with the
total amount going up by 10.113 billion yuan over the beginning of
the year, and by 2.653 billion yuan over the first six months of
l995.
</P>
<P>
Of the total short-term loans, industrial loans grew by 4.962
billion yuan over the beginning of the year and went up by 2.652
billion yuan over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, Beijing's Industrial and Commercial Bank and five
local enterprises have signed agreements to jointly run banks in a
bid to serve large and medium-sized state firms.
</P>
<P>
Local bank loans going to agriculture went up by 19.2 percent
over the first half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
Loans going to commercial firms, architectural enterprises,
foreign trade enterprises and foreign-funded firms all increased
by different degrees.  
</P>
