<HEADLINE> S'pore Business Circle Mixed on Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore business circle
was mixed in their business expectations for the second half of
this year, as the country's economic growth moderated in the first
six months, according to an economic survey released today by the
Ministry of Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Survey for the second quarter revealed that
industrialists were less optimistic about business conditions for
the second half of 1996. But, with the exception of real estate
services, establishments in commerce and services were generally
positive over business conditions ahead.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturers who posted a 6.3 percent growth in the second
quarter, way below the first quarter's 14 percent, were much less
positive over the business outlook ahead, results of the survey
showed.
</P>
<P>
However, it said that a net weighted balance of five percent of
the establishments expected business to improve. "This is largely
due to the recent moderation in global electronics demand, which
has affected the business expectations of establishments in the
electronics industry," it commented.
</P>
<P>
The less optimistic sentiments were reflected on key indicators
like output and new orders, which were expected to be less
favorable, it said. In addition, it said that price competition
and the strong Singapore dollar remained the most important
factors limiting export orders.
</P>
<P>
Within the commerce sector, wholesalers, retailers and
hoteliers expected better conditions ahead while restaurateurs
expected unfavorable conditions, it said.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, establishments in the real estate industry
were relatively pessimistic, while financial institutions
continued to expect favorable business conditions for the next six
months, the Ministry said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
