<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Nepal to Review Border Issue over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Nepali coalition
government has decided to review a controversial border issue
after ruling parties joined the opposition to criticize its
negligence over the alleged Indian encroachment of Nepal's
territory.
</P>
<P>
An all-party team, probably led by Foreign Minister Prakash
Chandra Lohani, is to make an on-the-site study later this week to
the border area in the eastern district of Jhapa, where local
people claimed that a new Nepal-India border pillar erected last
month was about one kilometer inside Nepal from the traditional
borderline.
</P>
<P>
The issue was raised late last month when local newspapers
reported that residents in the eastern border town of Bhadrapur
were worried about the recent demarcation move and angry with the
government's silence to their complaints.
</P>
<P>
It was reported some new border pillars were set up after local
border officers of Jhapa district and the neighboring Indian
district of Kisangunj signed some border documents early last
month.
</P>
<P>
Some lawmakers of the main opposition party the Communist Party
of Nepal (CPN-UML) later in the parliament accused the government
for its ignorance to the alleged Indian encroachment and demanded
it to look into the issue immediately.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a press release of the Indian embassy here on July
25 refuted the local press reports of the Indian encroachment,
saying that "it is India that had lost some territory as a result
of the rationalization of the boundary."
</P>
<P>
Then over one week ago came a public statement by Foreign
Minister Lohani to clarify the government's stance on the
controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
Lohani said in the statement that the new border markers were
built in line with a 1816 treaty signed by Nepal and the then
British-ruled India.
</P>
<P>
The recent demarcation work was approved by a Nepal-India joint
team of border officers, he said, adding that the work of erecting
new border pillars started four years ago and is expected to
continue for three more years.
</P>
<P>
He said an old pillar on the east side of Mechi river set up in
1818 by the British-Indian government was not a demarcation mark
but a reference one. The 1816 Nepal-India treaty recognizes Mechi
river as the boundary.
</P>
<P>
The new pillar erected last month was about 1 kilometer west of
the river because the river was continuously changing its course
during the last 180 years, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Nepal and India agreed to fix the border in 1988 in accordance
with a 1874 border map, resulting in the recent demarcation work,
according to the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
But his statement failed to calm down the opposition's
suspicion of the Indian encroachment instead to attract criticism
over the government's stance on the issue even from lawmakers of
ruling parties.
</P>
<P>
MPs of the main ruling Nepali Congress (NC) party and the
ruling partner National Democratic Party (RPP) lately in the
parliament accused the government of turning a blind eye to the
Indian encroachment, describing Lohani's earlier statement of
ignoring the ground reality.
</P>
<P>
Local residents in the border area were also angered by the
foreign minister's statement, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Lohani said Sunday that an all-party team will go to the
eastern border area to find out the ground reality, indicating the
government is ready to reconsider its position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
It is expected the inspection team, also involving technical
experts, will make its border trip Friday after the foreign
minister returns from his three-day India visit starting today.
</P>
<P>
However, Lohani is not expected to raise the border issue to
the Indian side during his visit, which aims at bilateral
discussions on issues like trade and transit, economic cooperation
and the Indian investment in Nepal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0096 </DOCNO>
