<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 10:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Sign Three Major Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Iran today signed
three major agreements, including a 20 billion dollar gas
deal, in defiance of a U.S. threat to impose tough sanctions on
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The multi-billion dollar gas contract was signed by Turkish
Energy Minister Recai Kutan and Iranian Oil Minister Gholamreza
Aqazadeh in the capital of Tehran only one week after
U.S. President Bill Clinton signed the D'Amato bill into a law to
punish non-American companies investing 40 million dollars or
more in oil and gas industries of Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted the gas deal by the two neighboring
countries indicates that the power politics does not work. No
countries would sacrifice their own national interests to
ingratiate themselves with the super power of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here say that it is the matter of trade
between the two countries and has nothing to with investment
or the American sanction law.
</P>
<P>
Besides the gal deal, the two agreements on prevention of
double-taxation and joint economic commission meeting were signed
by Recai Kutan and Iranian Roads and Transport Minister Akbar
Torkan.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin Erbakan and Iranian First
Vice-President Hassan Habibi were present at the signing
ceremony held in former Sadabad Palace.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the two neighboring countries claimed that
the signing of the multi-billion dollar gas deal will mark a
new chapter in the relations between Ankara and Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The pro-Islamic Turkish prime minister said at the press
conference that "we signed three agreements today and began a new
trend in the ties between the two countries."
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed to begin construction of pipeline
immediately. It is an agreement good for Iran," he added.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old Turkish prime minister said: "We have tried
to raise the level of trade in economic exchanges to the
highest level up to 2.5 billion dollars from the present low
level of less than 1 billion dollars," he added.
</P>
<P>
To achieve this purpose, he added, "We signed a document on
elimination of double-taxation and we have put 100 million
dollars at the disposal of our banks to get trade moving."
</P>
<P>
Iranian Oil Minister Aqazadeh told Xinhua that Iran will
begin to transfer three billion cubic meters of gas to Turkey
from 1999 and the amount will increase to 10 billion cubic
meters from 2005.
</P>
<P>
Based on the 22-year-long accord, Iran will build a
260-kilometer pipeline from the vicinity of Tabriz, northwest
Iran, to the Turkish border within three years and a half. The
total gas pipeline will be 1,500 kilometers from Tabriz to
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
Aqazadeh said that Turkey will make the payment in cash
while Iran would be getting an annual profit of about one
billion dollars from the gas sales a year.
</P>
<P>
Iranian First Vice-President Hassan Habibi said that the
agreements were the results of an emergency meeting of the two
countries' joint economic commission.
</P>
<P>
He said that the amount of the trade and economic
exchanges should go beyond 2.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
He assured the visiting Turkish prime minister that Iran
will buy more goods from Turkey. "We have decided to
procure our needs from Turkey and the Islamic countries first
rather than distant and strange countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 250-member Turkish delegation has wrapped up its two-day
visit to Iran. They will continue their 10-day trip to
Pakistan, Singapore, Indonesia and Malaysia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
