<HEADLINE> Singapore Revises 1996 Economic Growth Down to 7-8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The government of Singapore
has revised its economic growth forecast for 1996 from 7.5 to 8.5
percent to 7 to 8 percent, the Ministry of Trade and Industry
(MTI) said today when releasing the Second Quarter Economic
Survey.
</P>
<P>
It said that growth in the country' economy moderated from the
revised 10.9 percent in the first quarter to 7 percent in the
second quarter due mainly to slower growth in external demand,
particularly for electronic products and components, thus making
growth for the first half of the year stand at 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that global economic prospects worsened
slightly during the period because of weaker sentiments in the
European Union (EU) and more moderate growth in Asia, though the
outlook for the United States and Japan remained good.
</P>
<P>
The global electronics industry was expected to show slower
though still healthy growth this year, it said, adding, however,
that with oversupply in key components like semiconductors and
inventory problems in other segments, output growth had slowed.
</P>
<P>
Forward-looking indicators like the Composite Leading Index and
business expectations surveys suggested that growth in the second
half was likely to slow down from the 8.9 percent seen in the
first half, it said.
</P>
<P>
But, the ministry also said that a short breather from the
above-potential growth rates experienced in the last three years
is, however, desirable in moderating cost increases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
