<HEADLINE> Commentary: Congress Urges Combined Efforts to Protect Earth (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Protection of the environment
and natural resources has been the top concern of 7,000 geologists
attending the current 30th International Geological Congress in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Key topics of previous sessions were placed on the evolution of
the earth and geological issues centering around mineral
prospecting, while the current session has devoted particular
attention to the relationship between the atmospheric layers, dike
set, continental structures and mankind, pushing earth sciences to
a multi-discipline study containing environmental protection, said
a IGC spokesman, who has attended the geological grand meeting for
four sessions running.
</P>
<P>
His conclusion was supported by the speech delivered by Peter
Cook, director of the British Geological Survey, entitled
"Sustaining our life supporting systems", and the speech of Kevin
Burke, professor at the University of Houston, USA, on the
advances in continental dynamics.
</P>
<P>
Papers delivered by 1,500 participants at the 150 academic
seminars touched on water, resources, environment and other
essential elements to sustain human life.
</P>
<P>
The congress has focused its attention on many key issues in
the forefront of geological study, including the influence of
atmosphere on people's daily life, changes of climate, evolution
of surface and underground water and improvement of geological
environment, said Zhang Zhiyi, deputy head of IGC's scientific
committee.
</P>
<P>
Geological disasters across the world claim 250,000 lives and
cause an economic loss of 40 billion US dollars each year. A
quarter of the population on earth live in an environment with the
amount of suspended solid surpassing required standards, the
congress was told.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
