<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Woolgrowers Call For Flexible Stockpile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Wool Council of Australia
(WCA), today called for a flexible wool release scheme in which
the amount of wool on the market from the wool stockpile could be
halved when prices sank.
</P>
<P>
Under existing legislation, 182,000 to 192,000 bales of wool
must be sold every three months, according to the fixed release
scheme, WCA President Rod Thirkell-Johnston told journalists here.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Canberra, WCA endorsed the option of a minimum
of 90,000 bales to be sold per quarter, with no maximum specified.
</P>
<P>
The president announced that woolgrowers wanted to aim for a
target to terminate the 2.2 million bales stockpile by December
31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ability to reduce the amount of wool available from the
stockpile would benefit struggling growers by allowing Wool
International to sell more in a rising market.
</P>
<P>
"The advantage of adopting this approach is that only 90,000
bales need to be sold in periods of weak demand while enabling
Wool International to sell more in firmer markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
An average of about 125,000 bales would need to be sold a
quarter to terminate the stockpile by the target date.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thai Electronics Exports: Situation and </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- With new projects and expansions
of electronic industries in Thailand, their products enjoy good
prospects for export while facing challenges ahead.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's electrical and electronic exports are worth about
400 billion baht (16 billion US dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
With a labor efficiency advantage and 16 producers, which
mainly produce for foreign orders, circuit boards are one of the
country's main item for export.
</P>
<P>
Facing a market difficulty as a result of a worldwide surplus
and plummeting prices, circuit boards exports are expected to
remain unchanged or slightly over last year.
</P>
<P>
With a combined capacity of 19 million hard disk drives per
year by four producing firms, Thailand claims to be the world's
second largest producer after Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Due to the expansion of Seagate and the relocation of IBM to
Thailand, the country's hard disk drive exports are expected to
rise in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Beside, two Taiwanese investors produce 48 million electronic
calculators per year, the largest in number in the region covered
by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN). Both firms
have plans to triple capacity in the near future.
</P>
<P>
Minebea Group of Japan, the world's largest producer of ball
bearings for electronic goods, keeps expanding its capacity in
Thailand and its exports expansion is kept in line with the world
demand for computer.
</P>
<P>
Five producers of refrigerator operating in Thailand have a
total capacity of five million units per year, most of which are
shipped to Japan.
</P>
<P>
As the world demand for high quality refrigerators grows, South
Korean producers will relocate their bases to Thailand to enjoy
lower labor costs.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Thailand, the second largest television sets
producer in ASEAN, after Malaysia, makes 9 million tv sets by 16
firms in the country.
</P>
<P>
However, this segment faces anti-dumping duties from the
European Union, forcing firms to produce computer monitors and
parts for export in the form of semi-knocked-down kits. Exports
this year are expected to be close to those of last year.
</P>
<P>
The country's only video player producer, World Electric Co.,
with a yearly output of six million units, is expected to cut back
its exports because the United States has withdrawn tariff
privileges and due to the economic slowdown in the U.S. and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the video player producer has adjusted its plan by
exporting more parts.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, with six major air-conditioner makers, has a combined
annual capacity of 2.52 million units, the largest in ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities remain stable for home electrical appliance
producers that have good relationships with supporting industries
to improve efficiency.
</P>
<P>
Although appliances still face trade barriers and high costs,
producers have turned to making more value-added items or to
exporting parts, while paying more attention to research and
development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
