<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Food Poisoning Discussed at Emergency Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- An emergency meeting has been held
by the Japanese Education Ministry with local education board
members to discuss how to prevent the further spread of a
food-poisoning epidemic caused by the O-157 strain of E. coli
bacteria, according to a Kyodo News Service report Monday.
</P>
<P>
Some 370 members of boards of education from all the 47
prefectures and 12 major cities attended the meeting at the Tokyo
Medical and Dental University, ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
Schools and school lunch manufacturers were called upon to take
measures to prevent food poisoning in the new term starting
September 2.
</P>
<P>
The measures include boiling vegetables and other food to kill
the bacteria, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time in 20 years an epidemic has been declared
under the 1897 Communicable Diseases Prevention Law, which allows
authorities to isolate patients and even set up traffic blockades
if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The food poisoning has occurred in all the prefectures except
Akita, northern Japan, and had affected 9,331 people as of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Nine people have died, while 338 are still in hospital, some
seriously ill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
