<HEADLINE> Middle East Peace Dominates Talks Between Saudi, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Middle East peace
process dominated the talks between Saudi Arabian King Fahd and
his Jordanian counterpart Hussein late Sunday, according to the
Kuwait News Agency (KUNA) today.
</P>
<P>
The two kings, in their first face-to-face talks after six years
of strained bilateral relations caused by the Gulf crisis in
1990, dealt with a host of issues of mutual concern, most notably
the latest developments on the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
They discussed in depth the process, particularly the deadlock
on the tracks of peace talks between Israel on one hand and
Syria, Lebanon and the Palestinians on the other.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein talked in length on his recent meetings with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Syrian President Hafez
Al-Assad and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in a bid to
break the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
The two kings' points of view are identical concerning the
peace process, the KUNA said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides expressed grave concern over Israel's schemes to
expand the Jewish settlements, its stand on the peace process and
its attitude on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also expressed their support for the outcome of the
recent Arab Summit in Cairo for continuing the peace process
according to the formula formed at the Madrid peace conference
held in 1991, especially the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
On the bilateral relations, the two kings evaluated latest
cooperation developments in various spheres. They are expected to
continue reviewing means of bolstering mutual cooperation through
specific programs and mechanisms later.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein has visited Saudi Arabia several times for the last
two years, but the highest Saudi leader he met then was Crown Prince
and First Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in Saudi Arabia Sunday on his second Saudi trip
in six months and this is considered essential for the
restoration of bilateral relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
