<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcanoes Doomed The Dinosaur: China Conference Told (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Who pushed the dinosaur, the
largest ever living animal on earth 115 million years ago, to
extinction? It is a hot issue at the current 30th International
Geological Congress taking place in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
And while many experts blame a calamitous meteorite for dooming
the monsters that stalked the earth, one American scientist has
come up with another theory for dispatching dinosaurs to the
history books.
</P>
<P>
American Professor Sankar Chatterjee from the Texas Technical
University claims that the extinction of the dinosaur and other
animals was caused by massive long-lasting volcano eruptions,
touched off by a fierce collision between the Indian Plate and
Seychelles Plate. The collision, he reasons, led to the spread of
obnoxious substances from the earth's mantle.
</P>
<P>
Professor Chatterjee was putting forward his theory during a
discussion on the extinction and revival of animals and plants
on earth.
</P>
<P>
The hypothesis that the dinosaurs became extinct due to plate
collision does not currently have great support, but is
intriguing, said Douglas H. Erwin, one of the moderators of the
seminar. He is also the curator of the Department of Paleobiology
of the National Museum of Natural History in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The current theory popular since the 1980s described the reason
in this way:
</P>
<P>
In the Cretaceous (about 120 million years ago), a meteorite
ten kilometers in diameter hit the earth at a tremendous speed,
giving rise to a dust covering the earth for several months. The
temperature was so low that plants perished in large numbers. The
dinosaur were unable to adapt to the sudden weather change and
they did not have enough food to live on.
</P>
<P>
This theory was based on the discovery that a large amount of
iridium exists in the earth layers formed in that period and such
substance, which are rare in the earth, are usually found in the
meteorites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Projects in Xinjiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 12 (Xinhua)-- Northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region has become one of the biggest beneficiaries of
China's new upsurge of economic development.
</P>
<P>
Thirty key projects have been, or will be built, in the
multi-ethnic region this year, costing 12.2 billion yuan. The
central government has provided 70 percent of the funds in
Xinjiang's construction.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the central government
allocated 2.1 billion yuan to Xinjiang, 3.2 percent over the
amount in last year's same period.
</P>
<P>
The region has gained the approval to build a number of key
projects in the fields of agriculture, power, railways and
petro-chemical industry, with each involving an investment of more
than one billion yuan, although the country is implementing a
macro-control policy nation-wide.
</P>
<P>
Among them are a cotton production base, a petro-chemical plant
in Tarim Basin and a 265-km-long express way between the region's
capital city of Urumqi and Kuitun.
</P>
<P>
In the past five years, statistics showed, Xinjiang has built
78 key projects costing 33 billion yuan, 60 percent of which were
funded by the central government.  
</P>
</TEXT>
