<HEADLINE> Siberia Explosion Caused by Extraterrestrial Collision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, AUGUST 12 (Xinhua) -- A massive explosion that hit
Siberia in 1908 was caused by an extraterrestrial material hitting
the Earth, two Chinese researchers announced today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They were giving their theory about the so-called Tunguska
Explosion for the first time in the international science
community. A Beijing conference was told that a mini-planet, one
kilometer in diameter, hit Siberia.
</P>
<P>
They based their conclusion on the angle of the abnormal
content of a chemical element.
</P>
<P>
Hou Quanlin is an associate research fellow with the Geophysics
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences. Ma Peixue is a
post-doctorate researcher in the Technology Physics Department of
Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
They announced their finding at the 30th International Geology
Conference now in session in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They discovered that the iridium content in the particles
resulting from the Tunguska Explosion was very high and much higher
than that in other matters on Earth.
</P>
<P>
In the explosion that occurred in the Tunguska area in central
Siberia, explosion particles flew to the stratosphere and spread
to all parts of the world. Particles were discovered as far away
as the Antarctic.
</P>
<P>
As no collision hole was ever found, scientists concluded on
the basis of large amounts of chondrites found at the site of the
event that the explosion occurred before the material hit the
Siberian surface.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the explosion is probably the largest of its
kind this century and that perhaps the only event in which a small
planet has hit the Earth this century.
</P>
<P>
In nuclear technology analytical laboratory, Hou and Ma
analyzed the 15 samples obtained from the Tunguska explosion event
layer. They received the samples from Moscow University.
</P>
<P>
They found that the content of iridium in the samples was very
high. Iridium is a very rare element on the Earth.
</P>
<P>
They thus drew the conclusion that the Tunguska explosion was
caused by an extraterrestrial material about one kilometer in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
Previously, some scientists thought that the explosion was a
nuclear explosion, others expressed the view that it was caused by
an anti-matter and still others agreed that it was caused by a
comet. Some assumed that the extraterrestrial material was the
spacecraft of an extraterrestrial life.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ma Peixue said, "Scientifically speaking, it is possible
that other planets contain life. Yet I think the Tunguska explosion
could not be caused by the spacecraft of an extraterrestrial
life. It was an explosion caused by a small planet." 
</P>
</TEXT>
