<HEADLINE> Sleeping Sickness Resurfaces in Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Sleeping sickness resurfaced in
south-eastern Uganda and claimed at least 15 people every month
since last January, "the New Vision" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Okoth, coordinator/director of the community-based Vector
Control Organization, told the newspaper that the most affected
areas are Busoga, Tororo and parts of Mbale District.
</P>
<P>
Sleeping sickness appeared in Uganda in 1987 and broke out
last January, Okoth said, adding that his organization received
the reports about the disease from treatment centers.
</P>
<P>
The vector control program, supported by external donors, had
achieved success in controlling the disease in the past, but it
faces financial problems now, Okoth added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
