<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Vows to Seek International Arbitration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) President Yasser Arafat has said he would resort to
international arbitration if the Israeli-Palestinian peace process
becomes deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
In his first interview with Israeli media in two years that
was broadcast on Channel 1 TV Sunday night, Arafat made the
remarks to urge the Israeli government to resume the peace process
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
He said that peace was not only "a Palestinian need, but an
Israeli need and international need."
</P>
<P>
Arafat reiterated that east Jerusalem should be the capital of
an independent Palestinian state and called on Israel to resolve
the dispute through discussions.
</P>
<P>
"In my opinion, in the final stage there will be an
independent (Palestinian) state, no doubt, or you are insisting
on occupying us. I am asking this to every Israeli citizen,"
Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
"If there is no agreement, we have the United Nations, we
have the Hague (International Court of Justice), we have the
co-sponsors (the United States and Russia), we have the (United
Nations) Security Council, and we have the Europeans," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We will go to arbitration. It (Oslo agreement) is an
international need. There is no choice but to carry on with
the peace process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the apparent ignorance of him by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Arafat claimed Netanyahu could not
continue doing so for he is the "most important figure in the
Middle East equation."
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also lashed out at the five-month
long closure on Palestinian territories and Israel's decision to
lift a four-year-old ban on expanding Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
"What do you expect from those who are facing confiscation
of land every day? They are eating from this land. How can
he (Israel) face himself alone while his neighbor is facing
starvation?" he said, warning the "closure and the starvation
have arrived at the red line."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli closure of the Palestinian self-rule areas has
barred Palestinians from their jobs inside Israel and led
reportedly to food shortage. The Palestinians angrily call it
"collective punishment."
</P>
<P>
Asked if he could stop the attacks against Israel by
Islamic Resistant Movement (Hamas) and Jihad if the closure
was lifted, Arafat said he had been doing the best, but
could not guarantee "100 percent efforts have 100 percent
results."
</P>
<P>
However, Netanyahu made it clear that Jerusalem was a
deadlocked issue in an interview published Sunday in a
Palestinian newspaper Al-Quds. He foresaw no agreement on
Jerusalem would be possible with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On a possible meeting with Arafat, Netanyahu repeated he
would only do so "when it is necessary." He also attempted
to downplay the significance of his decision concerning
settlement expansion, saying he was talking about "the natural
expansion."
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalled since
May after Netanyahu won the victory in the Israeli general
elections, and the hardline policies adopted by the Netanyahu
government dimmed the prospects of future peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
