<HEADLINE> Zanzibar Raises Producer Price for Cloves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zanzibar government
has raised producer price for cloves to boost production of the
cash crop.
</P>
<P>
The Zanzibar State Trading Corporation (ZSTC) officer Hassan
Shoka told reporters on Sunday that one kilogram of first grade
clove will fetch 320 Tanzania Shillings (about O.53 U.S. Dollar)
instead of 250 T.Shs (0.42 Dollar), while second grade will be
bought for 280 T.Shs. (0.46 Dollar) a kilogram, up from 225
T.Shs.(0.37 Dollar).
</P>
<P>
The price of third grade clove has gone up by 50 T.Shs (0.08
Dollar) to 220 T.Shs. a kilogram while the fourth grade will
attract 150 T.Shs. (0.25 Dollar) per kilogram instead of 120
T.Shs. (0.2 Dollar).
</P>
<P>
This season, Zanzibar expects a bumber harvest of about 10,000
tonnes to 12,000 tonnes. The ZSTC projects to buy 9,000 tonnes of
cloves worth 2,700 million T.Shs. (4.5 million Dollars) from
growers.
</P>
<P>
Clove price in the world market has been irregular for years,
forcing Zanzibar to diversify its mono crop economy.
</P>
<P>
The clove price has dropped drastically, from more than 9,000
U.S. Dollars per tonne in 1982 to less than 1,000 U.S. Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Zanzibar, clove is also grown in Indonesia, Brazil
and Indian Ocean Islands of Comoro, Mauritius and Madagascar with
production figures reaching over 60,000 tonnes per year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
