<HEADLINE> Indian Court Hears Petition of Former Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Delhi, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Indian Supreme Court today
began hearing the petition of former prime minister P. V.
Narasimha Rao in connection with the cheating case of 100,000 US
dollars involving the UK based non-resident Indian businessman L.
Pathak.
</P>
<P>
The special leave petition was filed by Rao in the Supreme
Court on July 31 against the July 30 order of Justice S. K.
Mahajan of the Delhi High Court, who upheld Chief Metropolitan
Magistrate (CMM) Prem Kumar's decision to summon Rao in the case
as a co-accused.
</P>
<P>
The Delhi chief metropolitan magistrate on August 2 rejected
the plea of Rao to defer the trial in the Pathak cheating case
till the disposal of his special leave petition by the Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
To dismiss Rao's petition seeking the quashing of the July 9
CMM order, Mahajan observed that the former prime minister could
approach the lower court for necessary remedies.
</P>
<P>
Pathak had testified before the CMM court that he gave 100,000
US dollars to controversial godman Chandraswami and his associate
to secure contracts for the supply of newsprint and paper pulp to
India on the assurance of Rao, who was the then external affairs
minister.
</P>
<P>
Both Chandraswami and his associate are now lodged in the Tihar
Jail under judicial custody for their role in the cheating case
and their bail applications have time and again been rejected by
courts.
</P>
<P>
Pathak had said that Rao, during a meeting with him on December
22-23, 1983, at a New York hotel, had assured him "your work will
be done." During the arguments before the high court, however, Rao
through his counsel Kapil Sibal had claimed that he was never in
the US on the alleged date of meeting with Pathak.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
