<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's Balance of Payments Surplus Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's balance of
payments surplus increased to 2.8 billion Singapore dollars (about
1.97 billion US dollars) in the second quarter, up from 1.8
billion Singapore dollars (about 1.3 billion US dollars) in the
previous quarter, the Ministry of Trade and Industry (MTI) said
today.
</P>
<P>
The improvement largely reflects a sharp turnaround in the
capital account balance, MTI said, noting that the capital account
surplus recorded a net inflow of 4.5 billion Singapore dollars
(about 3.17 billion US dollars) compared to a net outflow of 7.8
billion Singapore dollars (about 5.57 billion US dollars) a
quarter ago.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the Ministry said the current account surplus
rose to 4.9 billion Singapore dollars (about 3.45 billion US
dollars), up from 4.3 billion Singapore dollars (about 3.07
billion US dollars) of the previous quarter.
</P>
<P>
In the April-June period, Singapore's growth in total trade
moderated, with the volume of trade increasing by 8.6 percent
compared with 17 percent a quarter ago, while in nominal terms,
total trade grew by 6.2 percent compared with 16 percent in the
January-March period.
</P>
<P>
MTI said that in nominal terms, imports grew by 5.9 percent and
was lower than the 17 percent in the previous quarter, while
exports increased by 6.5 percent, down from 14 percent three
months ago.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic exports rose by 5.2 percent, down from 13
percent in the previous quarter, while domestic exports of oil,
however, grew by 23 percent, the same as a quarter ago, the
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
It said the United States, the European Union, Malaysia, Japan
and Hong Kong took in 76 percent of Singapore's non-oil domestic
exports in the second quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore's non-oil domestic exports to the United States and
Japan were expected to continue to grow, though at slower rates,
whereas those to Hong Kong and Malaysia would continue to decline,
the Ministry said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
