<HEADLINE> India's Interest Rates To Stay High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
New Delhi, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Governor C. Rangasrajan of the
Reserve Bank of India (RBI) has said that money market rates would
rise and that the government's difficult borrowing program would
keep up the pressure on interest rates.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the local English newspaper
Business Standard, which was published today, the RBI governor
said short-term money market rates were "unduly low."
</P>
<P>
"These rates will firm up at more normal levels in the second
half," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the government's borrowing program, Rangarajan said,
"Although the gross and net market borrowings of the union
government in 1996-97 are marginally lower than in 1995-96, in
absolute amount they are still high, making it difficult to place
them in the market. The high level of market borrowing is putting
pressure on interest rates."
</P>
<P>
India's foreign exchange reserve must not be allowed to drop
below the present level of 17.9 billion US dollars, and the
current account deficit to go beyond 2 percent of GDP, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
