<HEADLINE> Lebanon to Treat Air-Pollution from Power Stations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's Minister of Water and
Electrical Resources Elie Hobeika has asked the government to
allocate 110 million U.S. dollars for a project of decreasing air
pollution from the three major power stations in the country.
</P>
<P>
The Eco News business weekly, which was issued today, said that
investigations conducted by the Lebanese Electricity Board (LEB)
at the Zouk power station, some 15 kilometers north of Beirut,
show that the level of pollution resulted from the power stations
is generally higher than the approved standards in Europe.
</P>
<P>
A report prepared by the LEB said that smokes emanating from
nearby factories and cars made the pollution worse in the Zouk
neighborhood. 
