<HEADLINE> Land Policy Threatens Food Security, Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe may put its internal
food security in danger if land is allocated to people who are
not able to use it to the full and contribute to national
development, Manicaland Provincial Governor Kenneth Manyonda said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The governor said people allocated land under the resettlement
program must utilize it to the optimum.
</P>
<P>
He reminded former freedom fighters who are currently being
allocated land under the resettlement program that they are
required to work hard and contribute to national food security.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out, "as a nation, we risk jeopardizing our
internal food security if land is allocated to people who are not
able to fully utilize it for whatever reason."
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, about 4,500 white farmers own about 70 percent of
the country's arable land. The government is enpowered to
compulsorily acquire land, mainly from white commercial farmers,
for resettlement of the largely landless blacks. 
</P>
