<HEADLINE> Thai Steel Importers Face Dumping Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 12 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government's
International Trade Department has agreed to investigate the cases
of operators importing steel products from Eastern European
countries to determine if they are engaged in unfair competition
by dumping steel on the Thai market.
</P>
<P>
The department's move comes in response to allegations and
complaints from local steel manufacturers that the current
oversupply of steel in the domestic market stems directly from
steel dumping on the part of Polish and other Eastern European
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
A source from the department was quoted today by the local
newspaper Business Day as saying that since Thailand has no steel
anti-dumping law, the World Trade Organization has suggested that
the Thai Commerce Ministry draft a provisional regulation as a
short-term measure against steel dumping.
</P>
<P>
Legislation prohibiting steel dumping has been drafted by the
Thai Commerce Ministry and is expected to be submitted to the Thai
cabinet for final approval within this month.
</P>
<P>
The source also said the ministry's officials are gathering and
analyzing data and information from importers suspected of dumping
in the steel market.
</P>
<P>
The Thai Commerce Ministry has a plan which calls for using
import tariffs to deal with importers who are found to be engaged
in unfair steel-dumping practices, said the source.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
