<HEADLINE> Nepali PM Stresses Consensus on National Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Sher
Bahadur Deuba has said that consensus has been maintained among
major political parties in the country on issues regarding
national interests.
</P>
<P>
Deuba told the Lower House Sunday that consensus was forged
among his Nepali Congress (NC) party, its ruling partner, the
National Democratic party (RPP), and the main opposition, the
Communist Party of Nepal (CPN-UML), for sustainable development of
democracy in the country.
</P>
<P>
On the recent hot Nepal-India border demarcation issue, he
reiterated that Nepal would not let even a single inch of its
territory to be encroached.
</P>
<P>
However, he maintained that the newly border pillars on Nepal's
 eastern border with India were constructed in line with a 1816
treaty between Nepal and the then British-Indian government,
suggesting that India did not encroach Nepal's territory.
</P>
<P>
It was Deuba's first statement on the controversial border
issue which has attracted criticism from the opposition and local
newspapers here against the government's negligence.
</P>
<P>
Earlier last week, Foreign Minister Prakash Chandra Lohani made
a similar statement in the parliament but failed to calm down the
opposition's suspicion of India's encroachment.
</P>
<P>
Lohani, however, said the government would try to ask India to
reexamine the border pillars to remove doubts concerning possible
technical mistakes.
</P>
<P>
Local residents in Nepal's eastern border area claimed that a
new Nepal-India border pillar erected last month was about one
kilometer inside the Nepali territory.
</P>
<P>
Lohani is leaving for India today for a three-day visit but
might not hold formal talks on the border issue with his Indian
counterpart I.K. Gujral.
</P>
<P>
Officials here said he is expected to discuss bilateral issues
such as trade and transit, economic cooperation and India's
investment in Nepal with Indian leaders.  
</P>
</TEXT>
