<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Economy Grows 7 percent in 2nd Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Growth in the Singapore
economy moderated to seven percent in the second quarter, down
from 10.9 percent a quarter ago, the Ministry of Trade and
Industry (MTI) announced today.
</P>
<P>
It attributed to lower growth to the slowdown in the global
electronics cycle arising from a moderation in demand and an
oversupply of components like chips.
</P>
<P>
This also affected the exports of regional economies, which in
turn, had knock-on effects in transport and communications, and
commerce, it said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry noted that the manufacturing sector grew by 6.3
percent, down from 14 percent a quarter ago, due largely, as it
said, to slower growth in electronics, which also affected
supporting industries like fabricated metals.
</P>
<P>
The personal computers, telecommunications, semiconductors and
consumer electronics were affected by weaker external demand and
keen competition, as well as transitional problems like a changing
product mix, it said.
</P>
<P>
The financial and business services sector expanded more slowly
at 6.5 percent, with the financial services sub-sector being
affected by sluggish performance in the stockbroking industry, due
to weak sentiments.
</P>
<P>
However, the ministry said, growth in domestic banks' credit
operations stayed healthy, while the business services sub-sector
continued to benefit from demand from headquarters services and
information technology services, as well as demand for commercial
and office space.
</P>
<P>
The transport and communications sector increased by 8.4
percent, as the sea transport sub-sector continued to slow down.
The commerce sector grew more slowly at 5.7 percent in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
The construction sector was an exception as it grew strongly by
14 percent in the three-month period. MTI said the growth was
boosted by the strong pipeline of projects in the last two years,
particularly in the public and private residential segments.
</P>
<P>
Residential construction work accounted for about 48 percent of
total certified payments in the second quarter, it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
