<HEADLINE> American Wheat with disease Intercepted in Qingdao </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Port quarantine officials in the
Chinese city of Qingdao have intercepted a consignment of
disease-infected wheat imported from the United States.
</P>
<P>
The grain has been detected as having bunt disease, said the
the local quarantine office for animals and plants in Qingdao, in
east China's Shandong Province,
</P>
<P>
The batch, weighing 46,000 tons, was imported by a Chinese
corporation. Bunt disease is listed as one of the most dangerous
crop diseases, with any commodities infected strictly denied entry
by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
The disease can cause crop losses of more than half, and a
sharp grain quality degradation. It can stay alive for six to ten
years in the soil.
</P>
<P>
Officials say it is the first time the Qingdao office has
detected the disease in more than ten years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
