<HEADLINE> Myanmar Leader Arrives in Kuala Lumpur for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Myanmar's
ruling state law and order restoration council Than Shwe arrived
here today for a five-day official visit to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Than Shwe, invited by Malaysian king Tuanku Ja'afar, will have
an audience with Tuanku and hold official talks with Prime
Minister Mahathir Mohamad later today.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will sign several agreements during Than
Shwe's visit which Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad
Badawi considered as "most significant" in the context of
Malaysia's constructive engagement with its neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar obtained the status of an observer of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) in July this year, which is the
prelude of it becoming a full ASEAN member. Malaysia is a member
of ASEAN which also groups Brunei, Indonesia, Singapore, Thailand,
The Philippines and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming the Myanmar leader's visit, Badawi said last night
the visit "represents a link in the ASEAN policy which Malaysia is
strengthening through constructive engagement".
</P>
<P>
He said "even though the visit is part of bilateral relations,
I also believe it is part of the policy of constructive engagement
and hence it is most significant and meaningful."  
</P>
