<HEADLINE> Russian PM Proposes State of Emergency for Chechen Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin proposed here today that a state of emergency should
be declared in the Chechen capital of Grozny in two or three days.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin put forward the proposal at an urgent meeting of
the State Commission for the Settlement of the Chechen Crisis to
discuss what had happened recently in Chechnya and ways to
normalize the situation there, according to the Russian news
agency Itar-Tass.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Chernomyrdin also empowered the Ministry of
Justice to make preparations for the imposition of the state of
emergency.
</P>
<P>
A total of 169 Russian soldiers have died and 618 injured in
the recent fighting provoked by Chechen militants on August 6,
officials announced at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, most parts of Grozny are still under the control of
the Chechen rebels. But the building of the branch of the Federal
Service of Security of Russia in the city center and hotels nearby
are under the control of the government troops, reports said.
</P>
