<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Takes Steps to Regulate Real Estate Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 12 (Xinhua) -- Beijing is to take measures to
standardize and improvement management of its real estate market,
according to today's "China Daily".
</P>
<P>
The paper said that a new regulation on real estate agents is
currently being drafted by the municipal government, according to
sources from a the city's administrative department for real
estate.
</P>
<P>
Real estate agent's services include consultation, appraisal
and brokerage of real estate.
</P>
<P>
In line with the relevant rules issued by the Ministry of
Construction, the new regulation -- which is expected to be made
public by the end of this month -- will stipulate the
qualifications of agents, management of agencies and their
businesses, as well as penalty clauses, said Liu Gang, a deputy
division chief of the Beijing Municipal Government Administration
of Real Estate.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, China's real estate development slowed
by an average of 10 percent. Growth climaxed at 123.3 percent in
June 1993 over June 1992. It dipped to 21.4 percent by the end of
last year, according to an official with the Ministry of
Construction.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that more houses were sold than were built
last year, experts fear the over-stocking of the market may
continue to expand this year and next. Tight credit, explosive
growth of supply, and extremely high housing prices that put off
private buyers are all negative factors.
</P>
<P>
A survey showed that commercial housing stock stood at 50.46
million square meters in floor space in 1995, an increase of 353.5
percent over 1994.
</P>
<P>
According to the magazine Chinese Real Estate, housing prices
in 1994 averaged 1,194 yuan (184 US dollars at the 1994 exchange
rate) per square meter.
</P>
<P>
But housing prices, ranging from 4,000 to 5,000 yuan (482 to
602 US dollars) per square meter in downtown Beijing, have now
risen beyond the reach of average households.
</P>
<P>
Many real estate agents have put profit first instead of the
legitimate rights and interests of consumers and developers.
</P>
<P>
They have undertaken illegal marketing, including false
advertising, to mislead buyers.
</P>
<P>
Effective measures must be taken to ensure the healthy
development of the market, "China Daily" quoted a local official
as saying.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has about 500 real estate broker firms with more
than 2,000 agents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0187 </DOCNO>
