<HEADLINE> Agassi Wins ATP Final for Second Consecutive Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Olympic titlist Andre Agassi
of the United States beat his fellow Michael Chang 7-6 (7-4), 6-4
Sunday to take the ATP Championship for second consecutive in
Mason, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, ranked seventh on the ATP Tour and seeded sixth here,
used a strong serve and powerful forehand strokes to beat the No.
3-ranked Chang, and collect the 320,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Agassi's Olympic victory over Spain's Sergi Bruguera
appeared to mark a revival from a year-long slump for Agassi since
his 1995 ATP victory.
</P>
<P>
He won at Key Bicayne this year, but he won seven ATP Tour
titles last year when he reached the world's No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's victory made Agassi the third player to successfully
defend his ATP Championship title. The others were Mats Wilander
in 1983 and 1984 and Chang in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
It was Chang's fourth consecutive year in the ATP
Championship's final round. He beat Sweden's Thomas Enqvist in
Saturday's semifinal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
