<HEADLINE> Christie Runs His Final Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Linford Christie of Britian ran
his final race and won the 150 meter competition in 15.05 seconds
at the Crystal Palace stadium on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, Christie, who confirmed he is quitting top-class
racing at the end of the season, ran the race before just 6,000
spectators -- one of the smallest crowds for an international
meeting there for years.
</P>
<P>
"All good things must come to an end," said Christie. "Next
year I'll be sitting in the crowd keeping dry."
</P>
<P>
The Britain's team captain lost his Olympic 100 meters title
after two false starts in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Tony Ward, spokesman for the British Athletic Federation,
said: "It (the meeting) was probably too close to the Olympics."
</P>
<P>
Tony Jarrett, who crashed out in the 110 meters hurdles heats
in Atlanta, outpaced Olympic and world champion Allen Johnson and
British team mate Colin Jackson in 13.32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Steve Backley won the men's javelin on countback after
finishing level with Australian Andrew Curry on 82.10 meters.
</P>
<P>
Fellow silver medallist Jonathan Edwards took the men's triple
jump with 16.93 meters -- his shortest winning leap for nearly two
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
