<DOCNO> XIE19960812.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1996-08-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Follow Balanced Policy in Gulf Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, August 11 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait said today it would
continue to follow a balanced foreign policy in the Gulf region
and will maintain normal relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with official Kuwait News Agency (KUNA),
Kuwaiti Ambassador to Washington Sheikh Mohammad Al-Sabah said
that Kuwait would not like to see confrontation between the
U.S. and Iran.
</P>
<P>
The sheikhdom would maintain normal relations with Iran despite
the fact that Tehran differs with the Gulf Cooperation Council
(GCC) over the control of three islands in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mohammad hoped that Iran would be a friendly rather
than a rival country due to its strategic, historic and religious
relations with the six GCC nations namely Oman, Qatar, Kuwait,
Saudi Arabia, Bahrain and the UAE.
</P>
<P>
He said any military confrontation between Tehran and
Washington could affect Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has listed Iran as a country that supports
terrorism. U.S. President Bill Clinton signed a bill recently to
enforce sanctions on foreign companies that invest in oil and gas
projects in Iran and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had hinted that several latest incidents that had
targeted the American lives and facilities may have been carried
out by Tehran-supported Islamic terrorists.
</P>
<P>
A blast in Saudi capital Riyadh last November targeted a
U.S. training complex killed five Americans. On June 25, a truck
bomb exploded in the eastern city of Khobar near Dhahran, Saudi
Arabia, claiming the lives of 19 U.S. airmen and injuring nearly
400 others.
</P>
<P>
On June 18, a TWA flight mysteriously exploded while heading
from New York for France, killing all the 230 people aboard. Seven
days later a pipe bomb went off in Centennial Park in Atalanta,
Georgia, amid the Atlanta Olympic games, killing two people and
wounding more than 100 others.
</P>
<P>
Iran has totally denied any involvement in these explosions.
</P>
<P>
Amid rising tension with Iran and in the wake of these
incidents, the U.S. has been carrying out a series of military
exercises in the Gulf region since the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
The move was aimed at what the U.S. officials said
demonstrating the quick-action capability of American forces in
the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
The military exercises code named Rugged Nautilus involves the
U.S. aircraft carrier Carl Vinson, the helicopter assault ship
USS Tarawa as well as an Air Expeditionary Force in Qatar,
reports said.
</P>
<P>
A flurry of military exercises and troops movements have
brought the number of U.S. military personnel in the region to
24,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
